1
00:00:37,401 --> 00:00:39,558
[Soft Spanish guitar melody]

2
00:00:48,740 --> 00:00:50,482
CLIFF: We got cenizo...

3
00:00:50,699 --> 00:00:52,821
...that's purple sage...

4
00:00:54,200 --> 00:00:56,358
...agave, nopal....

5
00:00:58,703 --> 00:01:00,196
What's that stuff?

6
00:01:01,203 --> 00:01:03,658
That's whatchamacallit.

7
00:01:06,581 --> 00:01:08,324
That's horse crippler.

8
00:01:10,499 --> 00:01:12,824
MIKEY: [Shouts] This place is a gold mine.

9
00:01:13,418 --> 00:01:14,828
Lead mine.

10
00:01:15,210 --> 00:01:16,324
MIKEY: What?

11
00:01:16,419 --> 00:01:18,327
I said it's a lead mine.

12
00:01:18,503 --> 00:01:20,625
MIKEY: Right.
CLIFF: Why am I talking to you?

13
00:01:20,713 --> 00:01:22,586
CLIFF: You got that thing on your head.

14
00:01:22,672 --> 00:01:24,913
You find lots of cactus and shit?

15
00:01:25,007 --> 00:01:27,211
Not just cactus. There's acacias...

16
00:01:27,382 --> 00:01:30,999
CLIFF: ...the yuccas....
MIKEY: Looks like a lot of cactus to me.

17
00:01:31,092 --> 00:01:35,836
Man knows 150 varieties of beer,
can't tell a poinsettia from a prickly pear.

18
00:01:37,054 --> 00:01:38,049
Cliff!

19
00:01:38,222 --> 00:01:41,553
CLIFF: You live in a place,
you should learn about it.

20
00:01:41,890 --> 00:01:44,379
CLIFF: Explore.
MIKEY: You've got to look at this.

21
00:01:46,225 --> 00:01:47,470
CLIFF: Don't tell me.

22
00:01:47,559 --> 00:01:49,515
Spanish treasure, right?

23
00:01:49,602 --> 00:01:50,680
Pieces of eight...

24
00:01:50,769 --> 00:01:53,010
...from the Coronado Expedition.

25
00:01:59,648 --> 00:02:00,846
Jesus!

26
00:02:17,406 --> 00:02:19,564
Was Coronado in the Masons?

27
00:02:20,658 --> 00:02:23,029
[Mexican mariachi music]

28
00:03:27,398 --> 00:03:30,847
SAM: The forensics fella's coming down
from San Marcos.

29
00:03:31,774 --> 00:03:35,438
There's no way to know how old
the body is without lab work.

30
00:03:35,651 --> 00:03:37,062
That ring?

31
00:03:37,319 --> 00:03:40,152
Mason's been around a long while.

32
00:03:41,779 --> 00:03:43,403
He a treasure hunter?

33
00:03:44,197 --> 00:03:45,738
Old bullets.

34
00:03:46,198 --> 00:03:47,857
Makes art out of them.

35
00:03:51,075 --> 00:03:54,110
CLIFF: [Shouts] Sheriff says
we shouldn't touch anything.

36
00:03:54,410 --> 00:03:56,401
He can't hear with that rig on.

37
00:03:56,578 --> 00:03:58,154
CLIFF: [Shouts] Mikey!

38
00:03:58,912 --> 00:04:00,536
Hey, what have we got here?

39
00:04:06,124 --> 00:04:08,993
SAM: We're supposed to leave everything
where we found it.

40
00:04:09,084 --> 00:04:10,910
They're real particular about that.

41
00:04:13,335 --> 00:04:14,995
The scene of the crime.

42
00:04:17,588 --> 00:04:20,338
No telling yet if there's been a crime...

43
00:04:22,882 --> 00:04:27,173
...but this country's seen a good number
of disagreements over the years.

44
00:04:37,473 --> 00:04:40,044
CELIE: He went to school on the post
when we were in Korea.

45
00:04:40,140 --> 00:04:43,056
It's all kids in the same boat, army brats--

46
00:04:43,892 --> 00:04:45,967
PILAR: His record shows
he's a good student.

47
00:04:46,059 --> 00:04:50,884
I'm more worried about the social thing.
Are there, like, gangs or guns--

48
00:04:51,061 --> 00:04:54,429
PILAR: We haven't had any
serious violence, if that's what you mean.

49
00:04:54,522 --> 00:04:57,889
But we've got a pretty lively mix.
Mexican kids...

50
00:04:57,982 --> 00:04:59,523
...anglo kids, black kids.

51
00:04:59,608 --> 00:05:02,441
CELIE: And the blacks are what?
PILAR: The smallest group.

52
00:05:02,525 --> 00:05:03,806
PILAR: Except for a couple...

53
00:05:03,902 --> 00:05:05,229
...of Kickapoo kids.

54
00:05:05,319 --> 00:05:08,234
Look, you're obviously a concerned parent.

55
00:05:08,737 --> 00:05:11,819
Chet has no history of getting into trouble.

56
00:05:12,030 --> 00:05:13,061
MOLLY: Pilar....

57
00:05:13,739 --> 00:05:14,853
Is Amado okay?

58
00:05:15,531 --> 00:05:16,860
He's not here?

59
00:05:16,949 --> 00:05:17,862
Is he sick?

60
00:05:19,241 --> 00:05:21,399
He's going to wish he was dead.

61
00:05:23,160 --> 00:05:25,864
[Loud Latin-American music plays on radio]

62
00:05:42,920 --> 00:05:45,077
Somebody hand me a CD player.

63
00:05:45,171 --> 00:05:47,044
[Speaks in Spanish ]

64
00:05:47,339 --> 00:05:51,085
TRAVIS: They've come a long way
since those old eight-tracks, ain't they?

65
00:05:51,174 --> 00:05:52,418
Something wrong?

66
00:05:52,508 --> 00:05:55,756
Stolen property. I'm hauling
the bunch of you to jail.

67
00:05:56,093 --> 00:05:59,045
If anything else is wrong,
tell me on the way to the station.

68
00:06:02,262 --> 00:06:05,345
HOLLIS: Cleaning his toenails
with a pocketknife.

69
00:06:05,430 --> 00:06:08,595
<i>He was the most hygienic</i>
<i>of all the McHenry's.

70
00:06:09,891 --> 00:06:13,092
<i>''Fishbait, '' Buddy says,</i>
<i>in that quiet way of his...

71
00:06:13,392 --> 00:06:17,222
...''what do you know about the tires
that went missing from Merkel's?''

72
00:06:17,394 --> 00:06:19,185
Fishbait thinks for a minute...

73
00:06:19,270 --> 00:06:22,269
...then lifts up a loose board
from the porch floor...

74
00:06:22,563 --> 00:06:24,555
...and calls down into it.

75
00:06:25,107 --> 00:06:28,189
''Come on out, Hooter, they caught us!''

76
00:06:30,192 --> 00:06:32,314
FENTON: Buddy Deeds, he had a way.

77
00:06:32,402 --> 00:06:35,566
He'd known who it was
from the tire tracks in the dirt...

78
00:06:35,653 --> 00:06:38,771
...leading from the back of the garage
to where they loaded up.

79
00:06:38,862 --> 00:06:40,272
''Old Fishbait,'' he said...

80
00:06:40,363 --> 00:06:44,109
...''never lifted a thing,
if there was a way he could roll it.''

81
00:06:46,157 --> 00:06:47,983
Never be another like him.

82
00:06:48,075 --> 00:06:50,529
You know that boy of his can't cut it.

83
00:06:50,785 --> 00:06:52,860
He's all hat and no cattle.

84
00:06:53,702 --> 00:06:54,782
Hey, fellas.

85
00:06:58,997 --> 00:07:01,035
We was telling a few on your old man.

86
00:07:01,123 --> 00:07:03,447
He was a unique individual.

87
00:07:03,624 --> 00:07:05,117
He was that.

88
00:07:05,875 --> 00:07:07,250
Big day coming up.

89
00:07:07,376 --> 00:07:10,624
I wish we'd have thought of it
while he was still living.

90
00:07:10,877 --> 00:07:12,335
Went so unexpected.

91
00:07:12,628 --> 00:07:14,536
FENTON: Better late than never.

92
00:07:14,796 --> 00:07:18,293
Korean War hero,
sheriff for nearly 30 years....

93
00:07:18,798 --> 00:07:21,370
The Buddy Deeds Memorial Courthouse.

94
00:07:21,466 --> 00:07:23,790
I heard there was a bit of a fuss.

95
00:07:25,051 --> 00:07:27,043
Well, the usual troublemakers.

96
00:07:27,302 --> 00:07:30,800
Danny Padilla from the <i>Sentinel</i>.
That crowd.

97
00:07:30,971 --> 00:07:34,587
We call everything else in the country
after Martin Luther King.

98
00:07:34,723 --> 00:07:38,006
We can't have one measly courthouse?

99
00:07:38,099 --> 00:07:39,676
King wasn't Mexican, Fenton.

100
00:07:39,766 --> 00:07:42,718
FENTON: Bad enough
that all the street names are in Spanish.

101
00:07:42,809 --> 00:07:44,599
They were here first.

102
00:07:44,727 --> 00:07:49,137
Then let's call it after Big Chief
Shit-In-The-Bucket. That Tonkawa had...

103
00:07:49,229 --> 00:07:50,603
<i>...the Mexes beat by centuries.

104
00:07:50,688 --> 00:07:53,604
Nineteen out of 20 people here
are Mexican.

105
00:07:54,565 --> 00:07:58,097
There was a faction pulling
for that boy killed in the Gulf War--

106
00:07:58,400 --> 00:08:00,226
Yeah. Santiago.

107
00:08:00,401 --> 00:08:02,689
Mexicans that know remember what...

108
00:08:02,777 --> 00:08:04,401
<i>...Buddy was for their people.

109
00:08:04,486 --> 00:08:06,692
<i>Hell, it was Mercedes over there</i>
<i>who swung...

110
00:08:06,779 --> 00:08:08,356
...the deciding vote for him.

111
00:08:09,405 --> 00:08:11,195
<i>She made it an even 3-3.

112
00:08:11,406 --> 00:08:13,896
As mayor, I get to cast the tiebreaker.

113
00:08:14,324 --> 00:08:18,818
The old-timers won't have a problem.
They know how Buddy come to be sheriff.

114
00:08:19,243 --> 00:08:20,902
Tell that story, Hollis.

115
00:08:20,994 --> 00:08:23,151
Everybody heard it a million times.

116
00:08:23,412 --> 00:08:24,905
I'd like to hear it.

117
00:08:25,830 --> 00:08:27,027
Your version of it.

118
00:08:27,372 --> 00:08:28,949
Yeah, come on, Hollis.

119
00:08:32,333 --> 00:08:33,612
Well, the two of us...

120
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:36,205
<i>...were the only deputies back then.

121
00:08:36,835 --> 00:08:39,076
Me and Buddy, in what, '58?

122
00:08:39,377 --> 00:08:41,168
'57, I think.

123
00:08:41,337 --> 00:08:44,917
The sheriff at the time
was big Charlie Wade.

124
00:08:46,089 --> 00:08:47,084
Charlie...

125
00:08:47,173 --> 00:08:51,418
...was one of your old-fashioned
bribe-or-bullets kind of sheriffs.

126
00:08:51,842 --> 00:08:55,589
He took a healthy bite out of whatever
moved through this country.

127
00:08:55,761 --> 00:08:57,752
HOLLIS: It was in here one night...

128
00:08:58,094 --> 00:09:00,549
<i>...back when Jimmy Herrera run the place.

129
00:09:00,929 --> 00:09:03,679
<i>Started over a basket of tortillas.

130
00:09:11,225 --> 00:09:14,972
This beaner fare doesn't agree with me
but the price sure is right.

131
00:09:17,103 --> 00:09:20,933
Jimmy got a kitchen full of wetbacks,
most of them relatives.

132
00:09:21,272 --> 00:09:23,430
Those people breed like chickens.

133
00:09:26,274 --> 00:09:27,305
So?

134
00:09:28,109 --> 00:09:32,186
I roust some <i>muchacho</i> on the street
with no papers, all he's got to say is:

135
00:09:32,277 --> 00:09:34,269
[In Spanish ] <i>I work for Jimmy Herrera.

136
00:09:35,987 --> 00:09:37,316
Sort of a...

137
00:09:37,489 --> 00:09:41,982
...I-scratch-his-back-he-washes-mine
arrangement, if you know what I mean.

138
00:09:43,949 --> 00:09:48,241
This'll be one of your pickups.
First of the month, like the rent.

139
00:09:48,702 --> 00:09:50,195
Get the car, Hollis.

140
00:09:57,539 --> 00:09:59,198
I'm not doing it.

141
00:10:04,876 --> 00:10:06,286
Come again?

142
00:10:07,211 --> 00:10:08,585
It's your deal.

143
00:10:09,711 --> 00:10:12,415
There's going to be some left over for you.

144
00:10:12,505 --> 00:10:13,998
I take care of my boys.

145
00:10:14,422 --> 00:10:16,414
That's not the point, Charlie.

146
00:10:16,882 --> 00:10:19,039
You feeling bad about Jimmy?

147
00:10:19,383 --> 00:10:24,292
Ask him how big a <i>mordida</i> they took
when he run a place on the other side.

148
00:10:24,718 --> 00:10:26,793
Those old boys from Ciudad León--

149
00:10:27,053 --> 00:10:28,630
I'm not picking it up.

150
00:10:30,638 --> 00:10:34,219
You do whatever I say you do
or else you put it on the trail, son.

151
00:10:41,435 --> 00:10:43,142
How about this, Charlie?

152
00:10:44,895 --> 00:10:48,345
How about you lay that shield
on this table and vanish...

153
00:10:49,438 --> 00:10:51,560
...before you end up dead...

154
00:10:51,815 --> 00:10:53,059
...or in jail?

155
00:10:57,442 --> 00:10:59,481
You're not making sense, Buddy.

156
00:10:59,568 --> 00:11:03,018
Stick around and I'm bringing up charges
on the county road project.

157
00:11:03,112 --> 00:11:05,898
Two-thirds of that money went straight
into your pocket.

158
00:11:09,407 --> 00:11:12,240
You're being mighty careless
with your mouth, son.

159
00:11:18,619 --> 00:11:21,618
You ever shoot a man
who's looking you in the eye?

160
00:11:32,376 --> 00:11:34,746
It's a whole different story, isn't it?

161
00:11:35,544 --> 00:11:37,085
You're fired.

162
00:11:37,753 --> 00:11:40,788
Not a soul in this county isn't sick to death
of your bullshit.

163
00:11:42,797 --> 00:11:45,667
Make yourself scarce and you'll make a lot
of people happy.

164
00:11:45,757 --> 00:11:47,381
-You little piss ant.
-Now...

165
00:11:47,466 --> 00:11:48,497
...or later.

166
00:11:50,092 --> 00:11:52,333
You won't have any trouble finding me.

167
00:11:56,387 --> 00:11:58,379
You're a dead man.

168
00:12:03,891 --> 00:12:06,889
WADE: Get the goddamn car.
We're going to Roderick's.

169
00:12:21,441 --> 00:12:22,602
[In Spanish ] <i>Boy...

170
00:12:22,983 --> 00:12:24,975
<i>...another beer, please.

171
00:12:29,153 --> 00:12:31,309
FENTON: Yeah,
that Buddy was a cool breeze.

172
00:12:32,362 --> 00:12:36,025
<i>Wade was known to put quite a few people</i>
<i>in the ground...

173
00:12:36,239 --> 00:12:39,274
<i>...and your daddy gets eyeball-to-eyeball</i>
<i>with him.

174
00:12:40,283 --> 00:12:43,151
HOLLIS: We made our pickup
at Roderick's place.

175
00:12:43,492 --> 00:12:46,326
<i>Nobody's seen hide nor hair of him since.

176
00:12:46,827 --> 00:12:51,404
He went missing the next day along
with $10,000 in county funds from the safe.

177
00:12:53,331 --> 00:12:55,121
<i>Never heard from him again.

178
00:12:55,207 --> 00:12:58,241
FENTON: Buddy Deeds said a thing,
he damn well backed it up.

179
00:12:59,292 --> 00:13:01,118
Never be another like him.

180
00:13:02,627 --> 00:13:06,753
So, I suppose then he arrested
all of Jimmy Herrera's people and...

181
00:13:06,837 --> 00:13:08,828
...sent them back to the other side?

182
00:13:10,922 --> 00:13:12,997
He came to an accommodation.

183
00:13:14,174 --> 00:13:18,251
Money doesn't always have to change
hands to keep the wheels turning.

184
00:13:19,509 --> 00:13:21,999
I know you had problems with your father.

185
00:13:22,928 --> 00:13:26,259
HOLLIS: And he and Muriel--
FENTON: Your mother was a saint.

186
00:13:27,430 --> 00:13:29,919
But Buddy Deeds was my salvation.

187
00:13:32,516 --> 00:13:34,554
Won't be another like him.

188
00:13:36,267 --> 00:13:37,844
DEL: It is an honor for me...

189
00:13:37,935 --> 00:13:39,760
...to assume command of this unit.

190
00:13:39,852 --> 00:13:42,259
I look forward to working with all of you.

191
00:13:42,354 --> 00:13:44,973
I'm sure you're all aware
of the Army's decision...

192
00:13:45,063 --> 00:13:46,770
<i>...to shut this post down.

193
00:13:47,439 --> 00:13:50,355
<i>That doesn't mean, however,</i>
<i>that we're here to mark time...

194
00:13:50,440 --> 00:13:52,147
...until we're reassigned.

195
00:13:52,983 --> 00:13:54,939
You may have heard rumors...

196
00:13:55,276 --> 00:13:57,564
<i>...that I run a very tight operation.

197
00:13:58,277 --> 00:13:59,770
These rumors...

198
00:14:00,153 --> 00:14:01,777
...are not exaggerated.

199
00:14:30,960 --> 00:14:33,959
[Rock music heard in distance]

200
00:14:48,677 --> 00:14:50,218
[Loud rock music]

201
00:16:03,503 --> 00:16:05,744
[Screams] Somebody call a doctor!

202
00:16:10,298 --> 00:16:11,755
[Screams]

203
00:16:12,466 --> 00:16:14,374
You weren't in here tonight, were you?

204
00:16:14,467 --> 00:16:15,628
No, no, sir.

205
00:16:15,842 --> 00:16:17,253
Go out the back way.

206
00:16:17,343 --> 00:16:20,212
ATHENA: [Screams]
Somebody call a doctor!

207
00:16:20,303 --> 00:16:22,460
[Athena continues screaming]

208
00:16:23,721 --> 00:16:25,380
Tearing everything down.

209
00:16:25,472 --> 00:16:30,096
Our heritage, the memory of the people
who fought and died for this land.

210
00:16:30,183 --> 00:16:32,636
We fought and died for this land too.

211
00:16:32,850 --> 00:16:35,174
We fought the U.S. Army,
the Texas Rangers--

212
00:16:35,268 --> 00:16:36,809
Yeah, and you lost.

213
00:16:37,478 --> 00:16:39,683
Winners get the bragging rights.

214
00:16:39,937 --> 00:16:44,762
People. It'd be best if we don't view this
in terms of winners and losers.

215
00:16:44,856 --> 00:16:47,689
The way she teaches,
she's got everything backward.

216
00:16:47,774 --> 00:16:49,895
I was on the textbook committee.
Her version--

217
00:16:50,317 --> 00:16:52,143
PRINCIPAL: We think of the textbook...

218
00:16:52,234 --> 00:16:54,356
...as a guide, not as an absolute.

219
00:16:54,486 --> 00:16:57,188
It is not what we set as the standard.

220
00:16:58,780 --> 00:17:01,529
Now, you people can believe
whatever you want...

221
00:17:01,614 --> 00:17:03,356
...but when it comes to teaching--

222
00:17:03,448 --> 00:17:07,574
They're our children too. As the majority
in this community, we have the right.

223
00:17:07,658 --> 00:17:12,650
The men who founded this state
have the right to have their story told.

224
00:17:12,869 --> 00:17:15,359
The men who founded this state
broke from Mexico.

225
00:17:15,454 --> 00:17:19,236
They needed slavery to be legal
to make a fortune in the cotton business.

226
00:17:19,331 --> 00:17:21,950
I think that's a bit of an oversimplification.

227
00:17:22,040 --> 00:17:25,621
-You reporting or running this meeting?
-Adding some historical perspective.

228
00:17:25,708 --> 00:17:27,996
You call it history, I call it propaganda.

229
00:17:28,085 --> 00:17:31,997
I'm sure they've got their own account
of the Alamo on the other side...

230
00:17:32,295 --> 00:17:35,211
<i>...but our schools shouldn't teach it</i>
<i>that way.

231
00:17:35,380 --> 00:17:36,459
Excuse me.

232
00:17:36,963 --> 00:17:41,956
I've only been trying to get across part
of the complexity of our situation here.

233
00:17:42,716 --> 00:17:47,293
Cultures coming together
in both negative and positive ways.

234
00:17:47,677 --> 00:17:50,712
If you mean food and music and all,
I have no problem.

235
00:17:51,638 --> 00:17:53,179
<i>But when you start changing...

236
00:17:53,263 --> 00:17:54,591
...who did what to who--

237
00:17:54,680 --> 00:17:58,094
We're just trying to present
a more complete picture.

238
00:17:58,474 --> 00:18:00,216
That's what's got to stop!

239
00:18:00,392 --> 00:18:04,802
There's enough ignorance in the world
without us encouraging it in school.

240
00:18:05,394 --> 00:18:08,062
Now, who are you calling ignorant?

241
00:18:08,479 --> 00:18:11,015
I hope the sucker dies.
Mess with me, that's what you get.

242
00:18:11,105 --> 00:18:13,143
Hospital says the kid is in bad shape.

243
00:18:13,231 --> 00:18:14,558
The shooter local?

244
00:18:14,648 --> 00:18:17,648
Houston. I think he knew the girl
from before.

245
00:18:17,983 --> 00:18:21,315
We'll take a statement from the GI's
before they go back to post.

246
00:18:21,402 --> 00:18:23,938
You can get the story from Otis.

247
00:18:24,528 --> 00:18:27,196
Any poop on the John Doe
we found today?

248
00:18:27,487 --> 00:18:31,649
No, nothing much.
Rangers put Ben Wetzel on it.

249
00:18:32,115 --> 00:18:33,608
SAM: I'll catch you later.

250
00:18:35,324 --> 00:18:37,280
[Soft Spanish guitar melody]

251
00:18:45,287 --> 00:18:47,777
PILAR: He's only 15. He's about 5 foot 5--

252
00:18:47,956 --> 00:18:48,951
SAM: Pilar.

253
00:18:51,749 --> 00:18:53,077
Something wrong?

254
00:18:53,333 --> 00:18:54,826
They've got my son.

255
00:18:55,001 --> 00:18:55,913
Here?

256
00:18:56,084 --> 00:19:00,993
Somebody called about a house that was
broken into. They say they don't have--

257
00:19:01,837 --> 00:19:04,124
All right, I know what he looks like.

258
00:19:04,255 --> 00:19:05,962
I'll see what's going on.

259
00:19:09,090 --> 00:19:10,288
I was....

260
00:19:12,718 --> 00:19:15,467
I was real sorry about Nando.

261
00:19:18,469 --> 00:19:20,094
He was a good fella.

262
00:19:24,305 --> 00:19:25,681
We haven't talked--

263
00:19:25,765 --> 00:19:27,970
We haven't talked since high school.

264
00:19:29,933 --> 00:19:30,964
Yeah.

265
00:19:31,435 --> 00:19:33,142
I'll go check on your boy.

266
00:19:36,603 --> 00:19:40,433
Ritchie didn't say nothing,
'cause he didn't want to get in it.

267
00:19:40,772 --> 00:19:44,981
Then, next thing I know
there's shots and Ritchie's down.

268
00:19:47,066 --> 00:19:49,105
You got some boys you run in earlier?

269
00:19:51,819 --> 00:19:54,735
They tell me you're good at fixing things.

270
00:20:00,614 --> 00:20:03,105
Your father was a hell of a mechanic.

271
00:20:07,826 --> 00:20:10,398
You know, if you figure minimum wage...

272
00:20:10,494 --> 00:20:13,162
...on the time most thieves spend in jail...

273
00:20:13,370 --> 00:20:16,370
...they could have bought
most everything they stole.

274
00:20:16,872 --> 00:20:20,287
They asked me to hook it up for them.
I didn't steal anything.

275
00:20:20,874 --> 00:20:22,996
Well, I didn't say you did.

276
00:20:25,376 --> 00:20:27,534
My name's Sam, by the way.

277
00:20:30,420 --> 00:20:32,412
SAM: He's all yours.
PILAR: Are you okay?

278
00:20:32,588 --> 00:20:34,579
What's the big deal?

279
00:20:34,672 --> 00:20:37,043
PILAR: You'll find out when I get you home.

280
00:20:37,132 --> 00:20:38,294
Thanks, Sam.

281
00:20:38,633 --> 00:20:40,209
It's no problem.

282
00:20:42,718 --> 00:20:44,295
It was good seeing you again.

283
00:20:51,764 --> 00:20:53,921
[Soft Spanish guitar melody]

284
00:21:11,523 --> 00:21:14,890
MIKEY: Big O's is the only place
where African American soldiers...

285
00:21:14,983 --> 00:21:16,809
...feel comfortable, sir.

286
00:21:16,984 --> 00:21:20,351
DEL: Have we had trouble there before?
CLIFF: Fistfight now and then.

287
00:21:20,444 --> 00:21:23,609
MIKEY: This town isn't much.
DEL: They didn't come for a vacation.

288
00:21:23,695 --> 00:21:27,643
MIKEY: For many, it's their first time away
from home, dealing with new people....

289
00:21:27,739 --> 00:21:30,229
MIKEY: I remember my first hitch--
DEL: Substance abuse?

290
00:21:30,324 --> 00:21:33,192
Yes, sir, but I went through the program.
I haven't drunk--

291
00:21:33,283 --> 00:21:36,034
DEL: I meant on the post.
How are you dealing with it?

292
00:21:36,117 --> 00:21:38,821
CLIFF: We throw a urine test at them
once a month.

293
00:21:39,161 --> 00:21:40,619
CLIFF: Random numbers...

294
00:21:40,787 --> 00:21:42,695
...maybe 100 people at a time.

295
00:21:42,788 --> 00:21:45,822
DEL: Let's make it once a week for a while.
CLIFF: Yes, sir.

296
00:21:45,997 --> 00:21:49,993
I sprint the last quarter mile.
You don't have to keep up.

297
00:21:50,500 --> 00:21:51,827
Appreciate it, sir.

298
00:21:57,503 --> 00:21:59,874
Guy cracks walnuts with his asshole.

299
00:22:00,296 --> 00:22:02,619
You get the feeling
he doesn't want to be here?

300
00:22:02,838 --> 00:22:04,664
[Mexican mariachi music]

301
00:23:00,825 --> 00:23:01,820
Sam the Man.

302
00:23:02,284 --> 00:23:04,986
Hey, Ben. Thanks for coming down.

303
00:23:07,244 --> 00:23:08,702
So, how's business?

304
00:23:09,370 --> 00:23:11,160
Business is booming.

305
00:23:11,746 --> 00:23:14,071
Got your drugs, got your illegals.

306
00:23:14,497 --> 00:23:18,659
Had a shooting the other night
at O's place. Soldier got ventilated.

307
00:23:19,166 --> 00:23:21,702
BEN: I hear they're closing Fort McKenzie.

308
00:23:21,792 --> 00:23:24,033
It'll pull a lot of jobs out of this county.

309
00:23:24,127 --> 00:23:28,502
We'll have folks swimming over to Mexico
to work in the sweat shops.

310
00:23:29,880 --> 00:23:31,539
Is that the word on our boy?

311
00:23:32,172 --> 00:23:33,500
This is Skinny.

312
00:23:34,257 --> 00:23:35,086
Skinny?

313
00:23:36,258 --> 00:23:39,008
When we find a body, it's Skinny or Stinky.

314
00:23:39,175 --> 00:23:41,582
Depends on how much meat's left
on the bones.

315
00:23:41,969 --> 00:23:43,592
SAM: That's a nice job.

316
00:23:44,678 --> 00:23:46,385
BEN: ''A male Caucasian...

317
00:23:47,180 --> 00:23:48,970
''...40 to 60 years old...

318
00:23:49,055 --> 00:23:50,679
''...5 foot 9...

319
00:23:50,848 --> 00:23:52,306
<i>''...5 foot 1 1.

320
00:23:53,016 --> 00:23:54,343
''Chewed tobacco.''

321
00:23:54,433 --> 00:23:57,053
Then we'll get the dental records
and personal effects.

322
00:23:57,143 --> 00:23:58,766
It's Charlie Wade.

323
00:23:59,935 --> 00:24:01,050
That badge....

324
00:24:01,145 --> 00:24:03,550
-Didn't come out of a cereal box.
-No.

325
00:24:13,984 --> 00:24:17,316
You know the popular version
of how he left town.

326
00:24:17,736 --> 00:24:20,189
Everybody on the border knows that story.

327
00:24:20,570 --> 00:24:22,229
You got a cause of death?

328
00:24:22,321 --> 00:24:23,566
BEN: Skull was intact.

329
00:24:23,655 --> 00:24:26,109
No signs of trauma on what we found.

330
00:24:26,406 --> 00:24:28,065
Not much to go on.

331
00:24:28,949 --> 00:24:33,027
So, he could have gone out to the post,
just hopped the fence...

332
00:24:33,534 --> 00:24:35,740
...dug into the dirt on the rifle range...

333
00:24:35,827 --> 00:24:37,653
...and had a heart attack.

334
00:24:41,872 --> 00:24:45,155
You remember what old Buddy carried
for a side arm?

335
00:24:46,333 --> 00:24:47,707
Colt Peacemaker.

336
00:24:47,791 --> 00:24:48,905
BEN: .45.

337
00:24:49,000 --> 00:24:50,198
He swore by it.

338
00:24:53,127 --> 00:24:54,157
What?

339
00:24:55,253 --> 00:24:56,746
I was just wondering.

340
00:24:59,755 --> 00:25:01,746
Is Buddy on your short list?

341
00:25:01,964 --> 00:25:05,711
If it were some poor <i>majadero</i>
who swam across, got lost in the brush...

342
00:25:05,799 --> 00:25:09,084
...and starved out there
it wouldn't go much further, but...

343
00:25:09,384 --> 00:25:12,005
...this is a once prominent citizen
who disappeared.

344
00:25:12,386 --> 00:25:15,670
You've got to investigate.
There's no question about it.

345
00:25:16,597 --> 00:25:20,758
I'll keep names out of it until we get
some answers or hit a dead end.

346
00:25:21,641 --> 00:25:26,216
You know how the press is when they get
ahold of a murder story, even 40 years old.

347
00:25:27,977 --> 00:25:30,645
Yeah, yeah. They can do a number on you.

348
00:25:34,814 --> 00:25:36,188
I remember...

349
00:25:36,564 --> 00:25:39,931
...Charlie Wade come
to my father's hardware store once.

350
00:25:40,024 --> 00:25:41,731
I was just a little boy.

351
00:25:42,734 --> 00:25:45,223
I'd heard stories
about how he shot this one...

352
00:25:45,318 --> 00:25:47,274
...how he shot that one.

353
00:25:48,737 --> 00:25:50,480
The man winked at me.

354
00:25:51,238 --> 00:25:53,063
I peed my pants.

355
00:25:54,489 --> 00:25:55,817
Winked at me.

356
00:25:57,574 --> 00:26:01,736
PILAR: The fight against the Spanish,
a bloody conflict for dozens of years...

357
00:26:01,827 --> 00:26:05,110
<i>...till they are finally defeated in 182 1...

358
00:26:05,370 --> 00:26:08,488
<i>...and Mexican independence is declared.

359
00:26:08,830 --> 00:26:12,161
<i>Anglo settlers are invited</i>
<i>to colonize the area.

360
00:26:12,331 --> 00:26:15,663
<i>By the time they begin the movement</i>
<i>against Santa Anna...

361
00:26:15,833 --> 00:26:19,164
...they outnumber the Mexicans here
by four to one.

362
00:26:19,709 --> 00:26:23,705
The war between Mexico
and the anglo forces ends...

363
00:26:23,795 --> 00:26:25,621
...in 1836...

364
00:26:25,963 --> 00:26:30,005
<i>...with the formation</i>
<i>of the Texas republic. Texas...

365
00:26:30,589 --> 00:26:32,248
...joins the United States...

366
00:26:32,340 --> 00:26:36,003
...as a state where slavery
is legal in 1845...

367
00:26:37,468 --> 00:26:41,167
<i>...after the so-called Mexican War,</i>
<i>then secedes to join...

368
00:26:41,387 --> 00:26:45,631
...the Confederacy in 1861.
The Confederacy is beaten...

369
00:26:45,972 --> 00:26:49,754
...and the Reformation period here
is marked by range wars...

370
00:26:49,849 --> 00:26:52,006
...and race wars and all this...

371
00:26:52,392 --> 00:26:54,549
<i>...paralleled by the constant battles...

372
00:26:54,643 --> 00:26:57,476
<i>...between the Mexican</i>
<i>and anglo settlers...

373
00:26:57,686 --> 00:27:01,267
...and the various Indian nations.
What are we seeing here, Chet?

374
00:27:04,148 --> 00:27:06,601
Everybody's killing everybody else?

375
00:27:15,528 --> 00:27:17,732
SAM: I always wondered
what you mayors do...

376
00:27:17,820 --> 00:27:19,646
...when you're not cutting ribbons.

377
00:27:20,905 --> 00:27:22,019
Sam!

378
00:27:24,866 --> 00:27:25,896
Partner.

379
00:27:26,825 --> 00:27:28,698
You caught me playing hooky.

380
00:27:29,325 --> 00:27:31,994
Floating around out here,
playing hell with them bass.

381
00:27:32,077 --> 00:27:33,985
Sounds great! Where do I sign up?

382
00:27:34,661 --> 00:27:37,151
HOLLIS: You been by your old place lately?

383
00:27:37,455 --> 00:27:38,568
No.

384
00:27:38,663 --> 00:27:40,785
New people painted it some awful color.

385
00:27:42,832 --> 00:27:45,950
We found a body out
by Fort McKenzie yesterday.

386
00:27:46,542 --> 00:27:48,166
It'd been there a long time.

387
00:27:48,251 --> 00:27:50,658
Was it Davy Crockett or Jim Bowie?

388
00:27:54,629 --> 00:27:57,628
You recall if Charlie Wade was a Mason?

389
00:27:58,506 --> 00:27:59,501
Charlie?

390
00:28:00,174 --> 00:28:03,623
I believe he used to go for Lodge meetings
over to Laredo.

391
00:28:04,842 --> 00:28:07,593
What's Charlie Wade got to do
with your body?

392
00:28:08,303 --> 00:28:11,385
All he was wearing was
a big old Masonic ring...

393
00:28:11,512 --> 00:28:13,670
...and a Rio County sheriff's badge.

394
00:28:21,100 --> 00:28:24,218
You remember anything else
from the last night you saw him?

395
00:28:24,310 --> 00:28:27,060
I told the story enough times.

396
00:28:28,312 --> 00:28:32,521
We were in the car. He was stewing about
his fight with Buddy as we drove over...

397
00:28:32,606 --> 00:28:34,432
<i>...to Roderick Bledsoe's.

398
00:28:34,690 --> 00:28:35,804
Bledsoe?

399
00:28:35,940 --> 00:28:38,265
He owned the colored roadhouse
before Otis.

400
00:28:38,359 --> 00:28:39,437
He's still living?

401
00:28:39,692 --> 00:28:40,854
No.

402
00:28:41,735 --> 00:28:45,778
I think his widow's still in their place
in Darktown, though.

403
00:28:47,363 --> 00:28:49,898
You think it was Charlie Wade, huh?

404
00:28:50,739 --> 00:28:52,777
Forensics people are sure of it.

405
00:28:55,033 --> 00:28:57,700
You got any idea
who might have put him there?

406
00:28:59,160 --> 00:29:01,116
Besides my father, I mean.

407
00:29:02,661 --> 00:29:04,819
There's no call for that, Sam.

408
00:29:05,537 --> 00:29:08,537
Wade made himself a pile of enemies
over the years.

409
00:29:08,997 --> 00:29:12,494
SAM: Buddy was one of them.
HOLLIS: The dedication's tomorrow.

410
00:29:12,957 --> 00:29:15,661
It's a hell of a time
to bring up old business.

411
00:29:16,250 --> 00:29:20,412
People have made this whole big thing
around my father. If it's built on a crime...

412
00:29:20,503 --> 00:29:22,162
<i>...they deserve to know.

413
00:29:22,712 --> 00:29:25,747
I understand why you might want
to believe he couldn't do it.

414
00:29:25,838 --> 00:29:28,957
I understand why you might want
to think he could.

415
00:29:37,803 --> 00:29:40,008
Thanks for your time, Hollis.

416
00:29:41,805 --> 00:29:43,132
Look at all this.

417
00:29:47,140 --> 00:29:48,598
Tackle, boat....

418
00:29:50,850 --> 00:29:53,091
All just to catch a little old fish...

419
00:29:53,185 --> 00:29:56,469
...minding his own business
down at the bottom of the lake.

420
00:30:00,021 --> 00:30:02,807
Hardly seems worth the effort,
does it, Sam?

421
00:30:07,358 --> 00:30:09,682
CLIFF: You knew this young man before?

422
00:30:09,859 --> 00:30:12,858
From back in Houston.
We both come up off the street.

423
00:30:12,944 --> 00:30:15,232
PRISCILLA: Did you know
he'd be there last night?

424
00:30:15,320 --> 00:30:18,071
If I had, I wouldn't have gone in.

425
00:30:18,530 --> 00:30:20,817
PRISCILLA: And you
and Private Graves were....

426
00:30:21,031 --> 00:30:22,774
We were just dancing.

427
00:30:23,950 --> 00:30:25,823
We're not running a dating service.

428
00:30:25,909 --> 00:30:27,652
ATHENA: I know that, Sergeant.

429
00:30:27,743 --> 00:30:31,157
We were just dancing.
There was a bunch of us there.

430
00:30:31,412 --> 00:30:34,992
Shadow...just come down
looking for trouble.

431
00:30:36,247 --> 00:30:39,614
I don't like to get involved
with soldiers' personal lives...

432
00:30:39,832 --> 00:30:42,119
...but when it interferes with training....

433
00:30:42,208 --> 00:30:44,615
Shadow just gets crazy.

434
00:30:45,459 --> 00:30:48,459
Sergeant, how is Ritchie doing?
Private Graves?

435
00:30:49,044 --> 00:30:50,242
He'll live.

436
00:30:50,504 --> 00:30:52,377
He'll be transferred to Fort Sam...

437
00:30:52,462 --> 00:30:53,873
<i>...as soon as he's stabilized.

438
00:30:53,964 --> 00:30:56,667
He'll probably be getting
a medical discharge.

439
00:30:58,924 --> 00:31:00,999
Will this go on my record?

440
00:31:02,342 --> 00:31:04,500
The incident will be noted.

441
00:31:05,052 --> 00:31:06,795
If it happened the way you say...

442
00:31:07,720 --> 00:31:09,877
<i>...there hasn't been an infraction.

443
00:31:10,013 --> 00:31:11,506
Thank you, Sergeant.

444
00:31:11,888 --> 00:31:12,968
CLIFF: You're dismissed.

445
00:31:13,056 --> 00:31:14,680
Thank you, Sergeant.

446
00:31:25,937 --> 00:31:27,845
You spoil them, Cliff.

447
00:31:28,438 --> 00:31:31,806
CLIFF: You don't believe her?
PRISCILLA: That wasn't an interrogation.

448
00:31:31,898 --> 00:31:34,648
I'm in charge of her sorry ass and frankly--

449
00:31:34,733 --> 00:31:38,230
I won't give her the third-degree
because her ex-boyfriend's a thug.

450
00:31:38,318 --> 00:31:41,104
She's pulled herself out
of a rough neighborhood.

451
00:31:41,194 --> 00:31:44,858
And if she isn't careful,
she's gonna slide right back into it.

452
00:31:53,992 --> 00:31:55,734
[Car door slams]

453
00:32:01,203 --> 00:32:02,613
SAM: Mrs. Bledsoe?

454
00:32:02,871 --> 00:32:04,033
That's me.

455
00:32:06,414 --> 00:32:08,038
I'm Sheriff Deeds.

456
00:32:09,749 --> 00:32:12,914
Sheriff Deeds is dead, honey.
You're just Sheriff Junior.

457
00:32:14,585 --> 00:32:16,909
Yeah, that's the story of my life.

458
00:32:17,502 --> 00:32:19,293
You ever play one of these?

459
00:32:22,422 --> 00:32:23,963
Yeah, I've seen them.

460
00:32:24,298 --> 00:32:26,751
MINNIE: Don't ever start up on them,
because...

461
00:32:26,840 --> 00:32:29,081
...once you do, you can't stop.

462
00:32:29,717 --> 00:32:34,092
I tell myself I'll just play
three little games after breakfast...

463
00:32:34,594 --> 00:32:36,253
...and here I am...

464
00:32:37,137 --> 00:32:39,176
...with half the day gone.

465
00:32:39,597 --> 00:32:42,382
May I ask you a few questions
about your husband?

466
00:32:43,140 --> 00:32:44,384
<i>Roderick.

467
00:32:44,515 --> 00:32:47,136
I ain't gonna say nothing bad
about the man...

468
00:32:47,351 --> 00:32:49,223
...but you can ask away.

469
00:32:49,976 --> 00:32:52,098
He had the club on Old Trail Road.

470
00:32:52,228 --> 00:32:54,848
We run that club for over 20 years.

471
00:32:55,437 --> 00:32:57,761
Give it over to Otis Payne...

472
00:32:58,397 --> 00:33:00,886
...in 1967, April.

473
00:33:02,358 --> 00:33:04,349
You must remember Sheriff Wade.

474
00:33:04,691 --> 00:33:06,020
Them days...

475
00:33:06,859 --> 00:33:09,812
...you deal with Sheriff Wade
or you didn't deal.

476
00:33:10,194 --> 00:33:12,600
First of the month, every month...

477
00:33:12,695 --> 00:33:15,268
<i>...he'd remind you</i>
<i>who you really working for.

478
00:33:16,656 --> 00:33:18,731
So, he squeezed money out of you?

479
00:33:19,491 --> 00:33:24,197
It wasn't legal to sell liquor in a glass
back then, unless you was a club, see?

480
00:33:26,244 --> 00:33:27,867
Roderick used to say:

481
00:33:28,203 --> 00:33:31,036
''Buy yourself a glass,
get a free membership.''

482
00:33:32,996 --> 00:33:34,111
MINNIE: Sheriff Wade...

483
00:33:34,414 --> 00:33:36,738
...he could close you down anytime.

484
00:33:37,541 --> 00:33:39,247
And my father?

485
00:33:40,792 --> 00:33:42,867
Sheriff Buddy was a different story.

486
00:33:42,960 --> 00:33:47,205
As long as Roderick throw his weight
the right way at election day...

487
00:33:47,629 --> 00:33:51,541
<i>...make sure all the colored come to vote,</i>
<i>throw a barbecue for the right folks....

488
00:33:51,630 --> 00:33:54,037
Sheriff Buddy kept to his word.

489
00:33:54,674 --> 00:33:56,630
That Sheriff Wade, though...

490
00:33:57,841 --> 00:33:59,465
...he could get ugly.

491
00:34:00,885 --> 00:34:02,509
People didn't complain?

492
00:34:03,511 --> 00:34:05,835
Not if you was colored or Mexican.

493
00:34:06,054 --> 00:34:08,211
Not if you wanted to keep breathing.

494
00:34:08,472 --> 00:34:11,804
I remember the last time I seen him
before he gone missing.

495
00:34:11,890 --> 00:34:14,178
He come fussing around our place.

496
00:34:14,516 --> 00:34:17,220
He used to come in
whilst we was in full swing.

497
00:34:17,893 --> 00:34:20,216
<i>Making everybody nervous.

498
00:34:20,561 --> 00:34:23,477
<i>Had him a smile like the Grim Reaper.

499
00:34:24,020 --> 00:34:27,056
<i>He used to sit there</i>
<i>with his hand on his old gun...

500
00:34:27,147 --> 00:34:29,897
<i>...acting the kingfish with everybody.

501
00:34:33,900 --> 00:34:35,180
<i>Otis Payne come...

502
00:34:35,276 --> 00:34:37,516
<i>...to work for us about that time...

503
00:34:38,902 --> 00:34:42,353
<i>...and that boy had him some attitude.

504
00:34:43,697 --> 00:34:45,439
[Loud rock music]

505
00:35:02,372 --> 00:35:03,367
Pour it.

506
00:35:04,874 --> 00:35:05,868
What?

507
00:35:06,541 --> 00:35:07,536
Pour it.

508
00:35:20,006 --> 00:35:21,084
I know you?

509
00:35:21,173 --> 00:35:22,417
Name's Otis.

510
00:35:23,424 --> 00:35:24,668
Otis what?

511
00:35:26,383 --> 00:35:27,414
Payne.

512
00:35:28,426 --> 00:35:29,836
They call me ''O.''

513
00:35:31,052 --> 00:35:32,711
One of Cleroe Payne's boys?

514
00:35:34,471 --> 00:35:36,628
I sent your daddy to the farm once.

515
00:35:38,389 --> 00:35:39,763
Yeah, I know that.

516
00:35:40,223 --> 00:35:41,882
Why you think that was?

517
00:35:43,683 --> 00:35:47,050
Some crop needed picking
and the man was short-handed.

518
00:35:48,478 --> 00:35:51,891
As I remember, it was 'cause
he had a sassy mouth on him.

519
00:35:52,062 --> 00:35:53,520
<i>Must run in the family.

520
00:35:54,730 --> 00:35:57,267
You wouldn't be running numbers
out of this club?

521
00:35:59,316 --> 00:36:01,438
Running numbers is illegal, sir.

522
00:36:01,692 --> 00:36:05,936
Running numbers without I knowin'
about it is both illegal and unhealthy.

523
00:36:06,319 --> 00:36:07,728
You remember that.

524
00:36:09,945 --> 00:36:11,652
<i>Son, you're not finished.

525
00:36:11,905 --> 00:36:13,018
Pour his.

526
00:36:13,739 --> 00:36:15,113
I prefer it in the bottle.

527
00:36:15,198 --> 00:36:16,573
WADE: Shut up, Hollis.

528
00:36:22,868 --> 00:36:24,610
How come you don't look familiar?

529
00:36:25,244 --> 00:36:27,200
I've been away, up in Houston.

530
00:36:28,038 --> 00:36:29,068
Houston?

531
00:36:29,330 --> 00:36:31,867
I hear they let you boys run wild up there.

532
00:36:32,706 --> 00:36:34,413
WADE: Look what you've done now.

533
00:36:34,707 --> 00:36:37,078
Better get something to wipe it up, son.

534
00:36:41,668 --> 00:36:44,205
You spilled it.
Maybe you should wipe it up.

535
00:36:52,216 --> 00:36:56,377
I told you to do something. Will you hop
to it or will we have a problem?

536
00:36:59,886 --> 00:37:02,838
You don't want to turn tail
in front of your people?

537
00:37:02,929 --> 00:37:04,303
I understand.

538
00:37:08,389 --> 00:37:10,714
Come on, Houston, give it a try.

539
00:37:11,225 --> 00:37:12,469
WADE: Come to Papa.

540
00:37:14,851 --> 00:37:16,131
RODERICK: Don't mind him.

541
00:37:16,227 --> 00:37:19,973
He's a bit slow, is all.
He don't mean nothing by it.

542
00:37:21,145 --> 00:37:22,723
That the problem, son?

543
00:37:23,021 --> 00:37:24,052
You slow?

544
00:37:25,064 --> 00:37:25,810
RODERICK: Otis!

545
00:37:26,689 --> 00:37:28,232
Apologize to the sheriff.

546
00:37:30,650 --> 00:37:33,400
Sheriff, you got him too scared to peep.

547
00:37:34,235 --> 00:37:36,226
Maybe if you'd put that gun up.

548
00:37:36,820 --> 00:37:38,229
You telling me what to do?

549
00:37:38,320 --> 00:37:40,110
No, Sheriff, I'm just....

550
00:37:40,238 --> 00:37:41,897
Is that whisky in them glasses?

551
00:37:44,115 --> 00:37:47,233
I'll have to cite you
for violation of a state law.

552
00:37:47,741 --> 00:37:50,231
This is a club, Sheriff. You've been here.

553
00:37:50,660 --> 00:37:53,327
You people better clear out of here now!

554
00:38:02,082 --> 00:38:04,204
Learn how to act your place, son.

555
00:38:05,917 --> 00:38:07,375
This isn't Houston.

556
00:38:12,044 --> 00:38:14,534
'Course, I was young...

557
00:38:15,547 --> 00:38:17,537
...and full of beans back then.

558
00:38:18,714 --> 00:38:22,959
I didn't understand the spot
I was putting Roderick in.

559
00:38:29,344 --> 00:38:32,297
And that was the last time you saw him?

560
00:38:34,013 --> 00:38:36,681
I think he came in one more time...

561
00:38:38,057 --> 00:38:39,800
...with Hollis and....

562
00:38:40,391 --> 00:38:42,596
No, no, your daddy wasn't with him.

563
00:38:42,851 --> 00:38:45,008
Made their monthly pickup.

564
00:38:45,728 --> 00:38:50,221
Roderick wasn't in, so I kept my mouth
shut and handed over that envelope.

565
00:38:51,479 --> 00:38:53,271
That was the night he disappeared?

566
00:38:55,732 --> 00:38:57,060
Could have been.

567
00:39:04,777 --> 00:39:06,058
You own a gun?

568
00:39:07,237 --> 00:39:08,150
Back then?

569
00:39:09,071 --> 00:39:10,150
OTIS: No.

570
00:39:11,531 --> 00:39:12,693
How about Roderick?

571
00:39:13,532 --> 00:39:14,811
Oh, he kept...

572
00:39:16,241 --> 00:39:20,735
...a big old piece back behind the bar,
just so folks knew it was there.

573
00:39:21,744 --> 00:39:23,735
I don't keep one here now.

574
00:39:24,454 --> 00:39:26,326
Don't much care for them.

575
00:39:27,955 --> 00:39:29,947
And when my father was sheriff?

576
00:39:30,248 --> 00:39:31,445
OTIS: What about him?

577
00:39:31,540 --> 00:39:33,282
What was your deal with him?

578
00:39:39,461 --> 00:39:42,295
Buddy was more part of the big picture:

579
00:39:43,629 --> 00:39:45,751
County political machine...

580
00:39:46,464 --> 00:39:49,132
...Chamber of Commerce, zoning Board....

581
00:39:50,799 --> 00:39:54,629
If I kept those people happy,
he was pretty much on my side.

582
00:39:55,093 --> 00:39:59,966
When somebody thought of starting up
a new bar for the black folks, they'd be....

583
00:40:01,929 --> 00:40:03,755
How should I say this?

584
00:40:04,181 --> 00:40:06,635
They'd be officially discouraged.

585
00:40:08,350 --> 00:40:10,341
He ever accept cash for a favor?

586
00:40:18,228 --> 00:40:21,679
I don't recall a prisoner ever died...

587
00:40:22,105 --> 00:40:24,097
...in your daddy's custody.

588
00:40:25,608 --> 00:40:27,895
I don't recall a man in this county...

589
00:40:28,108 --> 00:40:30,230
...black, white, Mexican...

590
00:40:31,194 --> 00:40:33,683
...who'd hesitate for a minute...

591
00:40:34,320 --> 00:40:38,018
...before they'd call on Buddy Deeds
to solve a problem.

592
00:40:39,405 --> 00:40:40,898
More than that...

593
00:40:42,658 --> 00:40:44,400
...I wouldn't care to say.

594
00:40:47,076 --> 00:40:50,324
I'm supposed to tell my friends
they're too low-class to hang with?

595
00:40:50,410 --> 00:40:51,406
Come on, Amado.

596
00:40:51,745 --> 00:40:53,571
'Cause I'm not like Miss Honor Roll?

597
00:40:53,663 --> 00:40:55,322
PILAR: Leave your sister out of it.

598
00:40:55,413 --> 00:40:57,488
You and those teachers in that dump....

599
00:40:57,581 --> 00:40:59,951
<i>Your story's over, so nobody can have fun.

600
00:41:00,040 --> 00:41:00,989
You jerk.

601
00:41:01,083 --> 00:41:02,991
You have no friends.

602
00:41:03,084 --> 00:41:05,159
Who'd be friends with a <i>pachuco</i> wannabe?

603
00:41:05,542 --> 00:41:07,748
I don't pretend I came on the Mayflower.

604
00:41:07,835 --> 00:41:09,459
PALOMA: And those stupid girls.

605
00:41:09,544 --> 00:41:10,659
Shut up.

606
00:41:10,754 --> 00:41:14,251
Joanie Orozco's telling the whole school
she's in love with Santo Guerra.

607
00:41:14,339 --> 00:41:15,251
So?

608
00:41:15,339 --> 00:41:17,911
You can't be desperately in love
when you're 14.

609
00:41:18,840 --> 00:41:21,046
<i>Not if you have half a brain in your head.

610
00:41:21,133 --> 00:41:22,792
Of course, you can.

611
00:41:23,426 --> 00:41:24,339
What?

612
00:41:24,802 --> 00:41:27,552
It's got nothing to do with being smart.

613
00:41:28,512 --> 00:41:31,084
It's ancient goddamn history, Danny.

614
00:41:31,263 --> 00:41:35,093
1963, they dam up the north branch
to make Lake Pescadero...

615
00:41:35,182 --> 00:41:37,174
...and a whole town disappears.

616
00:41:37,266 --> 00:41:38,510
A squatter's town!

617
00:41:38,600 --> 00:41:43,093
People lived in Perdido for over 100 years!
Mexicans and Chicanos are deported...

618
00:41:43,185 --> 00:41:47,050
...forcibly evicted by our local hero,
Buddy Deeds, and his department.

619
00:41:47,229 --> 00:41:49,434
There was a bill from the state legislature.

620
00:41:49,522 --> 00:41:52,770
Families were split apart!
A whole community was destroyed!

621
00:41:52,898 --> 00:41:57,225
And who gets Lakefront property
bought for a fraction of the market price?

622
00:41:57,567 --> 00:42:01,563
Buddy Deeds, Sheriff of Rio County,
and his Chief Deputy, Hollis Pogue.

623
00:42:02,361 --> 00:42:03,736
Are you finished?

624
00:42:05,196 --> 00:42:07,069
Look, I'm not after you, Sam.

625
00:42:07,489 --> 00:42:11,105
I just think people ought to know
the full story on Buddy Deeds.

626
00:42:13,574 --> 00:42:15,116
That makes two of us.

627
00:42:19,244 --> 00:42:23,536
What's the big deal? Go back over,
talk to the man, and bury the hatchet.

628
00:42:23,621 --> 00:42:26,988
DEL: Why me? He's had almost 40 years
and I haven't heard from him.

629
00:42:27,081 --> 00:42:28,539
He was probably embarrassed.

630
00:42:28,623 --> 00:42:31,908
DEL: Otis Payne was never embarrassed
about a thing in his life.

631
00:42:32,166 --> 00:42:34,039
You were 8 when he left.

632
00:42:34,293 --> 00:42:37,495
He moved three houses down
with my mother's best friend.

633
00:42:38,044 --> 00:42:39,124
Dad.

634
00:42:39,837 --> 00:42:42,078
''Delmore, where's your daddy?''

635
00:42:42,213 --> 00:42:45,876
Godforsaken town.
Everybody in everybody else's business.

636
00:42:46,090 --> 00:42:47,832
Everybody loved Otis. Big ''O.''

637
00:42:47,924 --> 00:42:51,172
Always there with a smile or a loan...

638
00:42:51,259 --> 00:42:54,175
-...or a free drink.
-Dad, can I talk to you about track?

639
00:42:54,261 --> 00:42:55,256
People change.

640
00:42:55,845 --> 00:42:57,042
Not that much.

641
00:42:57,137 --> 00:42:58,133
I talked to the coach.

642
00:42:58,221 --> 00:43:00,508
I told you. Next year,
if your grades are high.

643
00:43:00,597 --> 00:43:01,842
I have a B average!

644
00:43:01,931 --> 00:43:04,716
How many B students do you think
they take at West Point?

645
00:43:04,807 --> 00:43:07,297
We'll be here for three years.
We'll have to see him.

646
00:43:07,975 --> 00:43:09,006
No, we don't.

647
00:43:11,977 --> 00:43:12,842
[In Spanish ]

648
00:43:19,106 --> 00:43:22,224
Get off the phone.
We've got a big wedding.

649
00:43:22,482 --> 00:43:23,395
PILAR: Mommy....

650
00:43:23,482 --> 00:43:24,478
MERCEDES: [In Spanish ]

651
00:43:27,818 --> 00:43:30,142
MERCEDES: They are getting stupider
every year.

652
00:43:30,236 --> 00:43:32,606
Maybe you're getting less patient.

653
00:43:33,195 --> 00:43:36,527
If they're going to survive,
they have to know how to work.

654
00:43:36,906 --> 00:43:39,478
PILAR: You hire illegals,
what do you expect?

655
00:43:40,073 --> 00:43:42,065
Nobody's illegal in my cafe!

656
00:43:42,450 --> 00:43:46,030
They've got green cards,
relatives who were born here.

657
00:43:46,452 --> 00:43:49,321
If they only had a little common sense,
I'd be happy.

658
00:43:49,411 --> 00:43:52,530
If you took more time training them,
you wouldn't have to--

659
00:43:52,622 --> 00:43:56,119
Did you come here to teach me
how to run my business?

660
00:44:04,211 --> 00:44:06,332
Do you want to take a trip...

661
00:44:06,461 --> 00:44:07,955
<i>...down south with us?

662
00:44:08,046 --> 00:44:10,121
<i>Maybe see where you grew up?

663
00:44:10,588 --> 00:44:11,999
Why would I want to go there?

664
00:44:12,088 --> 00:44:13,547
PILAR: You must be curious...

665
00:44:13,632 --> 00:44:17,544
...how it's changed. Amado is
into this big <i>tejano</i>-roots thing...

666
00:44:19,051 --> 00:44:21,753
<i>...and I've never been further</i>
<i>than Ciudad Leön</i>.

667
00:44:21,968 --> 00:44:23,675
You want to see Mexicans?

668
00:44:23,844 --> 00:44:25,966
Open your eyes and look around you.

669
00:44:26,262 --> 00:44:28,218
We're up to our ears in them.

670
00:44:30,306 --> 00:44:31,633
Mommy...

671
00:44:33,557 --> 00:44:36,261
...how old were you when my father died?

672
00:44:37,226 --> 00:44:38,600
He was killed.

673
00:44:39,227 --> 00:44:41,017
Right, when he was killed.

674
00:44:42,770 --> 00:44:45,342
A little older than Paloma is now.

675
00:44:46,271 --> 00:44:48,179
How come you never remarried?

676
00:44:49,856 --> 00:44:51,848
It just didn't happen.

677
00:44:53,442 --> 00:44:54,770
<i>There must have been...

678
00:44:54,859 --> 00:44:56,021
...somebody.

679
00:44:57,485 --> 00:44:58,944
I was too busy.

680
00:45:01,487 --> 00:45:03,562
Nobody is too busy.

681
00:45:04,197 --> 00:45:05,275
MERCEDES: Maybe now.

682
00:45:05,572 --> 00:45:07,694
It was different back then.

683
00:45:08,199 --> 00:45:11,198
I had to do all the shopping,
all the cooking....

684
00:45:11,534 --> 00:45:15,529
What do I need some <i>chulo</i> with grease
under his nails to drink up the profit?

685
00:45:16,702 --> 00:45:17,616
Thank you.

686
00:45:17,912 --> 00:45:19,191
I don't mean Fernando.

687
00:45:20,579 --> 00:45:23,248
When I brought him home,
those were your exact words:

688
00:45:23,331 --> 00:45:25,406
''A <i>chulo</i> with grease under his nails.''

689
00:45:25,499 --> 00:45:26,660
I never said that.

690
00:45:26,749 --> 00:45:29,582
You made it pretty damn clear.
You thought he was nobody.

691
00:45:30,543 --> 00:45:32,581
I thought you could do better.

692
00:45:32,752 --> 00:45:34,245
What? What?

693
00:45:35,586 --> 00:45:39,119
Become a nun? You didn't even want me
to go out with anglos.

694
00:45:39,213 --> 00:45:41,750
I never said that. Just that boy.

695
00:45:42,923 --> 00:45:44,251
''That boy.''

696
00:45:45,508 --> 00:45:47,749
Say his name, for Christ's sake.

697
00:45:50,927 --> 00:45:53,334
You people are stealing from me.

698
00:45:54,136 --> 00:45:55,879
[Shouts in Spanish ]

699
00:46:00,557 --> 00:46:02,347
[In Spanish ] <i>Is she your mother?

700
00:46:04,433 --> 00:46:05,843
[In Spanish ] <i>I'm sorry.

701
00:46:06,184 --> 00:46:08,853
Now, I'm as liberal as the next guy.

702
00:46:09,185 --> 00:46:11,391
If the next guy is a redneck.

703
00:46:12,229 --> 00:46:13,687
But I got to say...

704
00:46:14,272 --> 00:46:17,555
...I think there's something
to this cold-climate business.

705
00:46:17,940 --> 00:46:20,429
I mean, you go to the beach...

706
00:46:20,899 --> 00:46:22,274
...what do you do?

707
00:46:23,401 --> 00:46:27,266
Drink a few beers, wait for that fish
to flop up on the sand.

708
00:46:27,611 --> 00:46:30,527
You can't build no civilization that way.

709
00:46:31,530 --> 00:46:33,817
But you got a cold winter coming on...

710
00:46:34,114 --> 00:46:35,737
...you got to plan ahead.

711
00:46:35,823 --> 00:46:38,443
That gives your old cerebral cortex
a workout.

712
00:46:38,533 --> 00:46:40,940
Good thing you were born down here then.

713
00:46:42,618 --> 00:46:46,068
You joke about it, Sam,
but we are in a state of crisis.

714
00:46:46,579 --> 00:46:49,447
<i>The lines of demarcation are getting fuzzy.

715
00:46:49,663 --> 00:46:53,659
To run a successful civilization, you've got
to have your lines of demarcation...

716
00:46:53,748 --> 00:46:56,950
...between right and wrong,
this one and that one.

717
00:46:57,667 --> 00:46:59,125
Your daddy understood that.

718
00:46:59,209 --> 00:47:01,201
<i>He was.... What do you call it?

719
00:47:02,002 --> 00:47:05,334
The referee in this damn <i>menudo</i>
we got down here.

720
00:47:05,795 --> 00:47:10,788
He understood how most folks don't want
their salt and sugar in the same jar.

721
00:47:11,882 --> 00:47:13,126
SAM: If you mixed drinks...

722
00:47:13,215 --> 00:47:15,041
...as bad as you mix metaphors...

723
00:47:15,133 --> 00:47:16,875
<i>...you'd be out of a job.

724
00:47:17,217 --> 00:47:20,087
You're the last white sheriff
this town will see.

725
00:47:20,303 --> 00:47:24,428
Hollis retires next year.
Jorge Guerra will take over.

726
00:47:24,888 --> 00:47:26,963
This is it, right here, Sam.

727
00:47:27,431 --> 00:47:32,339
This bar is the last stand.
<i>Se habla</i> American, goddamn it!

728
00:47:33,642 --> 00:47:36,214
And even in here, it's sliding away.

729
00:47:37,935 --> 00:47:40,342
Take that pair over there in the corner.

730
00:47:42,313 --> 00:47:45,099
COD Y: A place like this, 20 years ago...

731
00:47:46,148 --> 00:47:49,681
...Buddy'd been on them.
He'd have went over there...

732
00:47:49,775 --> 00:47:51,600
<i>...and given them a warning.

733
00:47:51,776 --> 00:47:55,771
Not that he had it in for the colored,
but just as a kind of a safety tip.

734
00:47:57,862 --> 00:47:59,569
Yeah, bet he would.

735
00:48:00,780 --> 00:48:02,439
The day that man died...

736
00:48:03,865 --> 00:48:06,271
...they broke the goddamn mold.

737
00:48:13,078 --> 00:48:15,116
PRISCILLA: Seriously.
CLIFF: Seriously?

738
00:48:15,453 --> 00:48:17,361
I think we should get married.

739
00:48:18,663 --> 00:48:20,322
We've been through this before.

740
00:48:20,414 --> 00:48:21,824
We should just do it.

741
00:48:21,915 --> 00:48:25,613
And if I get transferred to another post?
Germany or Korea?

742
00:48:26,042 --> 00:48:27,583
I'd ask for a transfer too.

743
00:48:27,667 --> 00:48:29,659
Which they'd most likely turn down.

744
00:48:29,752 --> 00:48:32,076
I'd quit the Army for you, if it came to that.

745
00:48:33,629 --> 00:48:35,455
You know, you are something.

746
00:48:35,797 --> 00:48:39,662
Man's going to retire in two years
and he offers to quit.

747
00:48:39,881 --> 00:48:41,506
Big goddamn deal.

748
00:48:42,216 --> 00:48:43,330
SAM: Excuse me.

749
00:48:43,674 --> 00:48:44,670
CLIFF: Sheriff.

750
00:48:45,385 --> 00:48:46,961
This is Sergeant....

751
00:48:47,302 --> 00:48:49,258
CLIFF: This is Priscilla Worth.

752
00:48:49,552 --> 00:48:52,469
Sheriff Deeds was with us
on our archeological find.

753
00:48:52,638 --> 00:48:54,629
They're building a shopping mall there?

754
00:48:55,430 --> 00:48:58,844
If certain people have their way,
it's gonna be a new jail.

755
00:48:59,557 --> 00:49:02,592
They're closing down military
and putting up jails...

756
00:49:02,683 --> 00:49:04,142
<i>...like 7-1 1 stores.

757
00:49:06,103 --> 00:49:10,180
Do either of you have any idea
when they stopped using that site...

758
00:49:10,270 --> 00:49:11,765
<i>...as a rifle range?

759
00:49:12,438 --> 00:49:14,596
Fort McKenzie stopped training infantry...

760
00:49:14,689 --> 00:49:18,353
<i>...there in the late '50s. It was just</i>
<i>a playground for the jackrabbits...

761
00:49:18,608 --> 00:49:21,228
...till they gave it to the county last year.

762
00:49:21,859 --> 00:49:23,566
You know who it was they dug up?

763
00:49:23,944 --> 00:49:25,520
Not for sure yet.

764
00:49:26,904 --> 00:49:28,895
But I kind of wish they hadn't.

765
00:49:33,949 --> 00:49:36,106
[Enrique speaks in Spanish ]

766
00:49:36,283 --> 00:49:39,864
In English, Enrique.
This is the United States.

767
00:49:40,201 --> 00:49:41,779
We speak English.

768
00:49:42,411 --> 00:49:44,486
Is very beautiful, your car.

769
00:49:44,995 --> 00:49:48,078
-Good night, Enrique.
-<i>Buenas noches, señora.

770
00:49:56,084 --> 00:49:58,656
[Soft Spanish guitar melody]

771
00:50:17,302 --> 00:50:19,874
[Soft pop song plays on juke box]

772
00:50:24,139 --> 00:50:25,253
OTIS: Carolyn....

773
00:50:26,348 --> 00:50:27,628
<i>Knock that off.

774
00:50:40,604 --> 00:50:42,063
Black Seminoles?

775
00:50:43,648 --> 00:50:45,106
Hobby of mine.

776
00:50:45,858 --> 00:50:47,267
A few artifacts...

777
00:50:47,734 --> 00:50:50,935
...couple of pieces one of your men
out on the base made.

778
00:50:51,652 --> 00:50:53,027
Admission's free.

779
00:50:58,905 --> 00:51:00,612
DEL: This is where he was shot?

780
00:51:02,324 --> 00:51:03,865
OTIS: He fell right by the door.

781
00:51:03,949 --> 00:51:05,490
You get much of that here?

782
00:51:07,284 --> 00:51:08,529
It's a bar.

783
00:51:09,535 --> 00:51:11,361
Folks come together...

784
00:51:11,995 --> 00:51:14,947
...drink, fall in love, fall out of love...

785
00:51:15,204 --> 00:51:16,947
...hear their grudges out.

786
00:51:17,372 --> 00:51:19,364
Deal drugs in the bathroom.

787
00:51:20,248 --> 00:51:22,323
If I thought it would do any good...

788
00:51:22,416 --> 00:51:24,953
...I'd put up a sign telling them not to...

789
00:51:25,293 --> 00:51:28,874
...right next to the one about
the employees washing their hands.

790
00:51:30,462 --> 00:51:32,003
This here is Carolyn.

791
00:51:33,255 --> 00:51:34,036
<i>Honey...

792
00:51:34,130 --> 00:51:36,798
...this is my son, Delmore.

793
00:51:39,341 --> 00:51:41,166
Nice to meet you, ma'am.

794
00:51:43,468 --> 00:51:46,302
I'll be in the back waiting for that delivery.

795
00:51:54,139 --> 00:51:55,135
So?

796
00:51:55,973 --> 00:51:56,969
So.

797
00:51:59,517 --> 00:52:02,433
Tell me why I shouldn't make
this place off-limits.

798
00:52:05,478 --> 00:52:07,386
This is an official visit then.

799
00:52:07,479 --> 00:52:10,847
I assume most of your business
is with our people.

800
00:52:13,857 --> 00:52:17,935
Your boys are cooped up together.
They need a place to let the steam out.

801
00:52:18,526 --> 00:52:22,225
If they're black, there's not but one spot
in this county...

802
00:52:22,320 --> 00:52:24,110
...where they feel welcome.

803
00:52:24,403 --> 00:52:26,063
It's been that way...

804
00:52:26,363 --> 00:52:28,271
...since before you were born.

805
00:52:28,364 --> 00:52:30,854
We have an enlisted man's club
at the post.

806
00:52:32,240 --> 00:52:34,647
You the man out there now, ain't you?

807
00:52:35,784 --> 00:52:37,064
It's your call.

808
00:52:37,868 --> 00:52:39,197
That's right.

809
00:52:41,662 --> 00:52:44,412
I've been hearing about
this new command out there...

810
00:52:44,497 --> 00:52:46,453
...for a couple of weeks now.

811
00:52:47,748 --> 00:52:50,499
The boys say they hear he's a hard case...

812
00:52:50,958 --> 00:52:53,282
...a real spit-and-polish man.

813
00:52:53,876 --> 00:52:56,579
<i>Full bird colonel by the name of Payne.

814
00:52:57,461 --> 00:52:59,749
Bet you never figured
you'd end up back here.

815
00:53:02,380 --> 00:53:05,130
When the Army offers you a command,
you go...

816
00:53:05,257 --> 00:53:06,631
...wherever it is.

817
00:53:07,633 --> 00:53:08,877
Right.

818
00:53:10,175 --> 00:53:11,290
I hear things too.

819
00:53:11,385 --> 00:53:13,044
They call you...

820
00:53:13,677 --> 00:53:15,633
...the mayor of Darktown.

821
00:53:17,054 --> 00:53:20,717
Over the years this is the one place
that's always been there.

822
00:53:21,138 --> 00:53:24,553
I loan a little money out,
I've settled a few arguments.

823
00:53:25,140 --> 00:53:29,599
I got a cot in the back. Folks get scared
to go home, they spend the night.

824
00:53:31,060 --> 00:53:34,059
There's not enough of us
to run anything in this town.

825
00:53:37,355 --> 00:53:39,347
It's the Holiness Church...

826
00:53:39,439 --> 00:53:40,683
...or Big O's.

827
00:53:42,482 --> 00:53:44,355
And the people make a choice.

828
00:53:45,775 --> 00:53:47,814
Most of them choose both.

829
00:53:48,652 --> 00:53:51,141
It's not like there's a borderline...

830
00:53:51,528 --> 00:53:53,982
...between the good people
and the bad people.

831
00:53:54,821 --> 00:53:56,101
<i>You're not on either...

832
00:53:56,197 --> 00:53:57,655
...one side or the other.

833
00:54:01,241 --> 00:54:02,272
Right.

834
00:54:04,993 --> 00:54:06,735
Will I meet that family of yours?

835
00:54:10,954 --> 00:54:12,862
Why would you want to do that?

836
00:54:13,663 --> 00:54:16,153
Because I'm your father.

837
00:54:24,168 --> 00:54:27,582
You'll get official notification
when I make my decision.

838
00:54:44,887 --> 00:54:46,296
So, that's him.

839
00:54:46,804 --> 00:54:48,297
Yeah, that's him.

840
00:54:49,722 --> 00:54:51,797
Historic occasion, ain't it?

841
00:54:51,890 --> 00:54:54,177
Seems like we have another one
every week.

842
00:54:54,266 --> 00:54:58,475
Jorge and the boys down at the Chamber
of Commerce got to keep things humming.

843
00:54:58,602 --> 00:55:00,261
Building up tourism, Sam.

844
00:55:00,352 --> 00:55:04,976
Most people come here to catch bass and
get laid at the Boy's Town in Ciudad León.

845
00:55:05,479 --> 00:55:09,771
You ought to put up a banner, ''Frontera,
Texas - Gateway to Inexpensive Pussy.''

846
00:55:09,857 --> 00:55:12,014
That kind of talk doesn't help.

847
00:55:12,983 --> 00:55:16,101
I'd rather have that
than a 10-foot-high catfish statue.

848
00:55:16,193 --> 00:55:19,027
Eddie Richter at the <i>Sentinel</i>
will kill that story.

849
00:55:20,236 --> 00:55:21,646
The Perdido thing?

850
00:55:21,778 --> 00:55:23,984
He agreed it wasn't exactly news.

851
00:55:24,822 --> 00:55:27,146
Danny will be out for blood the next time.

852
00:55:27,239 --> 00:55:31,152
That's why we need to talk to you
about the new jail.

853
00:55:31,325 --> 00:55:33,482
Come on, we don't need a new jail.

854
00:55:33,784 --> 00:55:35,408
That's a matter of opinion.

855
00:55:35,493 --> 00:55:38,777
SAM: We're already renting cells
to the Feds for their overflow.

856
00:55:38,912 --> 00:55:43,821
It wouldn't be your construction company
who'd get the bid on building this thing?

857
00:55:45,207 --> 00:55:46,451
SAM: And, Jorge....

858
00:55:47,625 --> 00:55:50,410
You wouldn't be thinking
about a couple dozen new jobs...

859
00:55:50,501 --> 00:55:54,033
...to dangle by the voters when you run
for mayor next election?

860
00:55:54,294 --> 00:55:57,210
Damn it, Sam! The people
are concerned about crime.

861
00:55:57,504 --> 00:56:00,290
I'm not gonna campaign
against your deal here.

862
00:56:00,672 --> 00:56:02,047
But if anybody asks...

863
00:56:02,131 --> 00:56:05,961
...I've got to tell them the truth.
We don't need a new jail.

864
00:56:06,217 --> 00:56:07,414
We backed you--

865
00:56:07,509 --> 00:56:10,425
When you backed me,
you needed somebody named Deeds...

866
00:56:10,511 --> 00:56:12,964
...to bump the other fella out of office.

867
00:56:16,138 --> 00:56:18,627
SAM: Hey, folks.
CITIzEN: Fenton, what's up, buddy?

868
00:56:18,972 --> 00:56:21,971
FENTON: How you doing?
SAM: Let's get this thing over with.

869
00:56:33,188 --> 00:56:36,637
MIKEY: I never thought I'd see
a buddy of mine dating a woman...

870
00:56:36,856 --> 00:56:38,894
...with three bars on her shoulder.

871
00:56:38,981 --> 00:56:40,938
CLIFF: It's beyond what you'd call dating.

872
00:56:41,024 --> 00:56:42,814
You're going to get married?

873
00:56:42,900 --> 00:56:43,896
CLIFF: Maybe.

874
00:56:43,984 --> 00:56:45,478
MIKEY: You met her family?

875
00:56:46,652 --> 00:56:49,272
They gonna be cool
about you being a white guy?

876
00:56:49,362 --> 00:56:54,104
Priscilla says they think a woman over 30
who's not married must be a lesbian.

877
00:56:54,739 --> 00:56:57,359
CLIFF: She figures they'll be so relieved
I'm a man....

878
00:56:57,449 --> 00:57:01,491
It's always heartwarming to see
a prejudice defeated by a deeper prejudice.

879
00:57:01,951 --> 00:57:04,322
But marriage, man, I don't know.

880
00:57:05,078 --> 00:57:06,275
Let's see....

881
00:57:06,495 --> 00:57:09,328
I did two tours of duty in Southeast Asia...

882
00:57:09,496 --> 00:57:11,820
...and I was married for five years.

883
00:57:12,331 --> 00:57:14,619
I couldn't tell you
which experience was worse.

884
00:57:14,706 --> 00:57:15,406
CLIFF: Mikey?

885
00:57:15,499 --> 00:57:18,333
I knew she was Japanese,
but she didn't tell me...

886
00:57:18,500 --> 00:57:20,291
...the Ninja-assassin part.

887
00:57:20,626 --> 00:57:23,828
Parents acted like I'd blow my nose
on their curtains.

888
00:57:24,878 --> 00:57:28,494
If I stayed out past 10:00,
she'd do a Madam Butterfly routine.

889
00:57:28,630 --> 00:57:30,372
Mikey, look at this.

890
00:57:30,965 --> 00:57:31,995
What?

891
00:57:32,090 --> 00:57:34,295
It's a bullet. I'm lousy with bullets.

892
00:57:34,383 --> 00:57:35,710
It's a .45.

893
00:57:37,051 --> 00:57:40,050
This is the stuff we picked up
the other day, right?

894
00:57:40,427 --> 00:57:43,592
-Rest of this is all .30 caliber.
-They used M-1s.

895
00:57:45,012 --> 00:57:48,546
CLIFF: So what's a pistol slug doing
on a rifle range?

896
00:57:50,182 --> 00:57:52,138
MIKEY: We'd better call that sheriff.

897
00:57:53,642 --> 00:57:56,179
Back in the early '70s...

898
00:57:56,977 --> 00:58:01,553
...a reporter from a national magazine
asked the governor of our Lone Star state:

899
00:58:01,979 --> 00:58:02,975
''Governor...

900
00:58:03,480 --> 00:58:05,057
<i>''...what's your ideal...

901
00:58:05,148 --> 00:58:07,767
<i>''...of what a real Texan ought to be?''

902
00:58:09,024 --> 00:58:10,304
<i>Governor said:

903
00:58:10,692 --> 00:58:12,315
<i>''Son, that's easy.

904
00:58:12,818 --> 00:58:14,097
<i>''Just go down to...

905
00:58:14,193 --> 00:58:16,066
<i>''...Rio County and look at...

906
00:58:16,153 --> 00:58:18,109
''...Sheriff Buddy Deeds.''

907
00:58:20,988 --> 00:58:22,150
Thank you.

908
00:58:22,613 --> 00:58:23,811
There's...

909
00:58:24,157 --> 00:58:26,990
...one more person
we ought to hear from and...

910
00:58:27,825 --> 00:58:31,488
...I think he's somebody that knew Buddy
better than any of us.

911
00:58:32,118 --> 00:58:33,114
Sam....

912
00:58:33,411 --> 00:58:34,738
Say a few words?

913
00:58:40,497 --> 00:58:43,580
Well, you folks who remember my father...

914
00:58:43,999 --> 00:58:45,825
...knew him as sheriff.

915
00:58:46,417 --> 00:58:49,665
But at home he was also judge, jury...

916
00:58:51,169 --> 00:58:52,627
<i>...and executioner.

917
00:58:55,296 --> 00:58:58,046
This is a real honor you're doing him today.

918
00:58:58,839 --> 00:59:03,713
If Buddy was around, I know his hat size
would be getting bigger every minute.

919
00:59:05,384 --> 00:59:10,008
I used to think there wasn't a place here
you could hide from my old man.

920
00:59:11,887 --> 00:59:13,510
And now I'm sure of it.

921
00:59:16,473 --> 00:59:18,464
<i>I do appreciate it, though.

922
00:59:19,348 --> 00:59:23,759
And wherever he is, Buddy's putting
the beer on ice for you. So, thank you.

923
00:59:28,187 --> 00:59:31,388
And now, my favorite council member...

924
00:59:31,646 --> 00:59:35,856
...and one of Frontera's
most respected businesswomen...

925
00:59:36,273 --> 00:59:38,478
...Mrs. Mercedes Cruz...

926
00:59:38,941 --> 00:59:40,518
...will do the honors.

927
00:59:44,986 --> 00:59:47,357
