Hey, Pete. How's it going?

1014
01:09:25,212 --> 01:09:26,871
Time marches on.

1015
01:09:27,047 --> 01:09:28,292
How much you got left?

1016
01:09:28,380 --> 01:09:29,839
Three months.

1017
01:09:31,049 --> 01:09:34,914
SAM: Stop growing that locoweed at your
place, you'd see more daylight.

1018
01:09:35,009 --> 01:09:37,499
PETE: It was for personal consumption.

1019
01:09:38,010 --> 01:09:40,880
You going to smoke an acre and a half
of marijuana?

1020
01:09:41,678 --> 01:09:44,797
PETE: I got a bad stomach.
It helps me to digest.

1021
01:09:44,889 --> 01:09:47,259
Your father never bothered me about it.

1022
01:09:47,640 --> 01:09:51,967
Leastways not till the drug people
got on his case in the late '60s.

1023
01:09:52,684 --> 01:09:55,352
SAM: I thought he busted you
a couple of times.

1024
01:09:55,518 --> 01:09:56,514
No.

1025
01:09:57,102 --> 01:09:58,478
Different charge.

1026
01:09:59,103 --> 01:10:00,513
PETE: I had a still.

1027
01:10:00,938 --> 01:10:04,186
Made my own mescal.
That's how come I ruined my stomach.

1028
01:10:04,731 --> 01:10:07,055
I'm surprised he bothered with it.

1029
01:10:07,149 --> 01:10:09,354
He was afraid I'd poison somebody.

1030
01:10:11,485 --> 01:10:13,890
Your father tried to do good for people.

1031
01:10:14,236 --> 01:10:16,061
-So I've heard.
-And your mother...

1032
01:10:16,153 --> 01:10:17,611
...she was a saint.

1033
01:10:18,238 --> 01:10:20,810
Remember that summer I built that patio
at your house?

1034
01:10:20,906 --> 01:10:23,193
She made me lunch every day.

1035
01:10:24,407 --> 01:10:25,901
You were working there.

1036
01:10:25,991 --> 01:10:28,860
It could have been another box lunch
from the jail.

1037
01:10:29,868 --> 01:10:33,200
So you built our patio
while you were on the county?

1038
01:10:33,620 --> 01:10:37,616
Out in the fresh air?
Nice gringo lady making you pies?

1039
01:10:37,789 --> 01:10:39,827
Who'd sit in that jail cell all day?

1040
01:10:41,707 --> 01:10:44,991
Sheriff Buddy, man.
[In Spanish ] <i>There's no one like him.

1041
01:10:45,209 --> 01:10:47,912
After that <i>cabrön</i>, Charlie Wade.

1042
01:10:48,001 --> 01:10:50,574
I heard Wade was a bit tough
on the Mexicans.

1043
01:10:55,338 --> 01:10:58,706
He murdered Eladio Cruz.
Is that tough enough for you?

1044
01:11:01,132 --> 01:11:02,377
Murdered him?

1045
01:11:02,551 --> 01:11:05,384
Chucho Montoya saw it with his own eyes.

1046
01:11:07,010 --> 01:11:08,634
Shot him in cold blood.

1047
01:11:08,719 --> 01:11:11,292
PETE: [In Spanish ]
<i>Charlie Wade was a big asshole.

1048
01:11:12,346 --> 01:11:13,295
RAY: Sam....

1049
01:11:16,223 --> 01:11:17,254
Wait up.

1050
01:11:21,976 --> 01:11:23,221
You're out early.

1051
01:11:24,769 --> 01:11:27,721
Haven't seen much of you at the jail lately.

1052
01:11:27,895 --> 01:11:30,136
SAM: Well, I'm working on a few things.

1053
01:11:30,730 --> 01:11:33,219
I'm going over to the other side.

1054
01:11:34,232 --> 01:11:35,511
Republicans?

1055
01:11:35,732 --> 01:11:37,226
No, Mexico.

1056
01:11:38,276 --> 01:11:40,066
Got to talk to someone.

1057
01:11:40,651 --> 01:11:42,393
They got telephones.

1058
01:11:42,569 --> 01:11:43,517
SAM: No.

1059
01:11:43,862 --> 01:11:45,604
It's got to be in person.

1060
01:11:48,822 --> 01:11:49,935
Sam, I....

1061
01:11:52,699 --> 01:11:54,073
The Committee....

1062
01:11:54,658 --> 01:11:57,148
Jorge and Fenton and all, they...

1063
01:11:57,742 --> 01:11:59,118
...they've asked me--

1064
01:11:59,201 --> 01:12:01,656
They want you to stand for sheriff
next election.

1065
01:12:03,287 --> 01:12:04,282
Yeah.

1066
01:12:05,913 --> 01:12:07,406
You'd do a good job.

1067
01:12:08,956 --> 01:12:09,987
Thanks.

1068
01:12:11,291 --> 01:12:12,570
What about you?

1069
01:12:13,208 --> 01:12:15,200
I don't know if I'll still want it.

1070
01:12:19,044 --> 01:12:21,534
I just didn't want to go around your back.

1071
01:12:21,671 --> 01:12:23,461
I appreciate you telling me.

1072
01:12:26,882 --> 01:12:28,458
You think we need a new jail?

1073
01:12:32,050 --> 01:12:33,425
Well, Sam....

1074
01:12:34,552 --> 01:12:36,709
It's a complicated issue.

1075
01:12:38,928 --> 01:12:40,091
Yeah, Ray.

1076
01:12:41,472 --> 01:12:43,547
You'd be a hell of a sheriff.

1077
01:12:52,435 --> 01:12:54,391
[Lively Mexican commercials on radio]

1078
01:13:37,207 --> 01:13:38,285
CHUCHO: Down here...

1079
01:13:38,373 --> 01:13:41,372
<i>...we don't throw everything away</i>
<i>like you gringos do.

1080
01:13:43,501 --> 01:13:45,077
Recycling, right?

1081
01:13:46,835 --> 01:13:48,413
We invented that.

1082
01:13:49,212 --> 01:13:52,081
The government doesn't have
to tell people to do it.

1083
01:13:54,589 --> 01:13:56,545
You own this place, huh?

1084
01:13:58,424 --> 01:13:59,800
This place...

1085
01:14:00,092 --> 01:14:02,083
...the one across the street...

1086
01:14:03,010 --> 01:14:05,582
...three or four others in Ciudad León.

1087
01:14:07,346 --> 01:14:09,302
[Speaks in Spanish ]

1088
01:14:10,222 --> 01:14:11,845
''King of the Tires.''

1089
01:14:13,932 --> 01:14:17,844
A lot of your people rolling over that bridge
on my rubber.

1090
01:14:18,309 --> 01:14:20,514
You lived in the States for a while?

1091
01:14:21,435 --> 01:14:22,431
Fifteen years.

1092
01:14:23,228 --> 01:14:25,053
Made some money, came back here?

1093
01:14:26,938 --> 01:14:28,265
Something like that.

1094
01:14:29,314 --> 01:14:32,895
Hey, you ever know
a fella named Eladio Cruz?

1095
01:14:35,942 --> 01:14:38,432
You're the sheriff of Rio County, right?

1096
01:14:39,236 --> 01:14:42,852
[Speaks in Spanish ]

1097
01:14:53,075 --> 01:14:54,698
Step across this line.

1098
01:14:58,494 --> 01:15:00,236
[Speaks in Spanish ]

1099
01:15:02,121 --> 01:15:04,741
You're not the sheriff of nothing anymore.

1100
01:15:05,748 --> 01:15:10,039
Just some <i>tejano</i> with a lot of questions
I don't have to answer.

1101
01:15:11,084 --> 01:15:12,660
<i>A bird flying south...

1102
01:15:13,543 --> 01:15:15,534
...you think he sees this line?

1103
01:15:16,253 --> 01:15:18,410
Rattlesnake,<i>jabalina</i>...

1104
01:15:19,421 --> 01:15:20,915
...whatever you got.

1105
01:15:21,880 --> 01:15:25,543
You think halfway across that line
they start thinking different?

1106
01:15:26,133 --> 01:15:27,756
Why should a man?

1107
01:15:28,800 --> 01:15:31,835
Your government's been pretty happy
to have that line.

1108
01:15:32,760 --> 01:15:35,250
The question's just been where to draw it.

1109
01:15:40,556 --> 01:15:43,509
My government can go fuck itself
and so can yours.

1110
01:15:45,516 --> 01:15:47,673
I'm talking about people here.

1111
01:15:47,851 --> 01:15:48,882
Men.

1112
01:15:53,353 --> 01:15:55,309
[Speaks in Spanish ]

1113
01:15:55,396 --> 01:15:56,771
Eladio Cruz...

1114
01:15:57,647 --> 01:16:01,310
<i>...is giving his friends a lift one day</i>
<i>in his</i> camión.

1115
01:16:01,566 --> 01:16:05,146
<i>But since they're on one side</i>
<i>of this invisible line and not the other...

1116
01:16:05,234 --> 01:16:08,068
<i>...they got to hide</i>
<i>in the back</i> como criminales.

1117
01:16:08,318 --> 01:16:12,148
<i>And because over there</i>
<i>he's just another Mex</i> bracero...

1118
01:16:12,362 --> 01:16:14,568
<i>...any man with a badge is his</i> jefe.

1119
01:16:14,655 --> 01:16:16,730
[Mexican mariachi music plays on radio]

1120
01:16:16,823 --> 01:16:17,818
ELADIO: [In Spanish ]

1121
01:16:20,199 --> 01:16:21,314
CHUCHO:

