WADE: [In Spanish ]

1152
01:19:17,825 --> 01:19:19,567
[Dramatic instrumental music]

1153
01:19:35,375 --> 01:19:36,785
MARISOL: Steve called for you.

1154
01:19:36,875 --> 01:19:37,870
Steve?

1155
01:19:38,167 --> 01:19:41,997
MARISOL: Steve.
Board of Education Steve, who likes you.

1156
01:19:42,753 --> 01:19:46,370
He goes for us hot-blooded Mexican girls,
I can tell.

1157
01:19:46,630 --> 01:19:49,298
Spanish. My mother would have
a heart attack.

1158
01:19:49,590 --> 01:19:51,546
Your mother's family is Spanish?

1159
01:19:51,632 --> 01:19:53,423
They go back to Cortés.

1160
01:19:53,508 --> 01:19:57,835
When he was riding by they were squatting
in a hut cooking hamsters for dinner.

1161
01:19:58,136 --> 01:20:01,752
You've got to be interested in somebody.
All you do is work.

1162
01:20:02,095 --> 01:20:05,130
All my mother does is work.
It's how you get to be Spanish.

1163
01:20:05,222 --> 01:20:06,929
How about this sheriff?

1164
01:20:07,348 --> 01:20:08,426
Sheriff?

1165
01:20:08,557 --> 01:20:10,845
The old high-school heartthrob sheriff?

1166
01:20:10,933 --> 01:20:13,139
I thought you were crazy about each other.

1167
01:20:13,226 --> 01:20:15,549
He's available. You're available.

1168
01:20:16,477 --> 01:20:18,966
I'm unmarried. I'm not available.

1169
01:20:19,145 --> 01:20:21,813
You told me one time it was true love.

1170
01:20:25,148 --> 01:20:27,685
Nobody stays in love for 23 years.

1171
01:20:29,734 --> 01:20:31,690
[Film soundtrack plays]

1172
01:21:05,209 --> 01:21:06,203
BUDD Y: Let's go.

1173
01:21:08,168 --> 01:21:09,282
BUDD Y: Goddamn it.

1174
01:21:10,753 --> 01:21:12,032
BUDD Y: Come here. Come on.

1175
01:21:12,128 --> 01:21:15,709
SAM: What the hell are you doing, asshole?
BUDD Y: How old is that girl?

1176
01:21:16,547 --> 01:21:18,669
HOLLIS: Get your clothes in order, missy.

1177
01:21:18,757 --> 01:21:20,298
BUDD Y: Where's your goddamn sense?

1178
01:21:20,382 --> 01:21:23,003
SAM: You got no fucking right!
Stay out of my life!

1179
01:21:24,051 --> 01:21:25,425
BUDD Y: Give me the keys.

1180
01:21:25,509 --> 01:21:27,133
HOLLIS: What should I do with her?

1181
01:21:27,219 --> 01:21:30,053
BUDD Y: Drive her home.
Tell her mother where we found her.

1182
01:21:30,262 --> 01:21:32,668
SAM: Leave her alone!
BUDD Y: Move it, boy!

1183
01:21:33,931 --> 01:21:35,887
[Car horns blaring]

1184
01:21:36,182 --> 01:21:38,505
PILAR: Don't tell my mother. She'll kill me.

1185
01:21:38,599 --> 01:21:39,595
SAM: Pilar!

1186
01:21:39,934 --> 01:21:41,343
BUDD Y: Don't eye me.

1187
01:21:41,434 --> 01:21:42,512
BUDD Y: Git!

1188
01:22:14,157 --> 01:22:17,359
[Soft rhythmic love song plays]

1189
01:24:38,267 --> 01:24:39,464
Follow me.

1190
01:25:05,905 --> 01:25:08,739
PILAR: We thought we were something,
didn't we?

1191
01:25:11,908 --> 01:25:12,939
Yeah.

1192
01:25:16,118 --> 01:25:18,739
And I look at my kids in school...

1193
01:25:19,661 --> 01:25:21,819
...10th, 1 1th-graders.

1194
01:25:23,413 --> 01:25:25,654
That's who we were. Children.

1195
01:25:30,458 --> 01:25:32,829
I mean, what did we know about anything?

1196
01:25:37,587 --> 01:25:38,665
Nothing.

1197
01:25:42,464 --> 01:25:44,254
When Nando died...

1198
01:25:46,466 --> 01:25:48,125
...it was so sudden...

1199
01:25:50,385 --> 01:25:52,956
...I kind of went into shock for a while...

1200
01:25:54,553 --> 01:25:56,959
...and then I woke up and...

1201
01:25:57,805 --> 01:26:02,464
...there was the rest of my life
and I had no idea what to do with it.

1202
01:26:10,477 --> 01:26:12,967
You know, the other day you asked...

1203
01:26:14,437 --> 01:26:16,144
...why I came back.

1204
01:26:16,897 --> 01:26:17,892
Yeah?

1205
01:26:20,982 --> 01:26:23,139
I came back 'cause you were here.

1206
01:26:45,244 --> 01:26:48,492
My mother hasn't changed a song
since I was 10.

1207
01:27:00,459 --> 01:27:03,458
[Soft Latin-American song plays
on juke box]

1208
01:29:11,145 --> 01:29:12,260
Wow.

1209
01:29:14,439 --> 01:29:15,766
Yeah.

1210
01:29:25,486 --> 01:29:27,643
How come it feels the same?

1211
01:29:30,029 --> 01:29:31,488
[Whispers] I don't know.

1212
01:29:32,489 --> 01:29:34,148
It just feels good.

1213
01:29:36,783 --> 01:29:38,110
Always did.

1214
01:29:46,120 --> 01:29:47,115
So....

1215
01:29:50,956 --> 01:29:53,493
What are we going to do about this?

1216
01:29:58,209 --> 01:29:59,240
More...

1217
01:30:00,418 --> 01:30:01,616
...I hope.

1218
01:30:31,183 --> 01:30:33,305
How long have you lived here?

1219
01:30:41,646 --> 01:30:42,844
Two years.

1220
01:30:43,814 --> 01:30:46,138
There's nothing on the walls.

1221
01:30:46,774 --> 01:30:48,148
No pictures.

1222
01:30:49,858 --> 01:30:51,268
I don't have kids.

1223
01:30:55,653 --> 01:30:57,230
Other pictures....

1224
01:30:58,988 --> 01:31:01,941
I don't know. It's nothing I want
to look back on.

1225
01:31:03,156 --> 01:31:05,029
Like your story's over.

1226
01:31:07,492 --> 01:31:09,318
I've felt that way...

1227
01:31:10,159 --> 01:31:10,989
...yeah.

1228
01:31:12,703 --> 01:31:13,816
It isn't.

1229
01:31:16,830 --> 01:31:17,991
Not by a long shot.

1230
01:31:22,666 --> 01:31:23,945
Pilar....

1231
01:31:28,626 --> 01:31:30,618
What was your father's name?

1232
01:31:31,628 --> 01:31:32,659
Eladio.

1233
01:31:33,671 --> 01:31:34,998
Eladio Cruz.

1234
01:31:36,338 --> 01:31:38,496
[Soft guitar chords play]

1235
01:32:25,528 --> 01:32:27,021
That's John Horse.

1236
01:32:28,155 --> 01:32:30,561
<i>The Spanish down in Florida call him...

1237
01:32:30,739 --> 01:32:32,150
...''Juan Caballo.''

1238
01:32:33,657 --> 01:32:34,901
John Horse.

1239
01:32:35,867 --> 01:32:37,574
He a black man or an Indian?

1240
01:32:37,659 --> 01:32:38,690
OTIS: Both.

1241
01:32:39,660 --> 01:32:41,569
OTIS: He was part of the Seminole nation.

1242
01:32:41,661 --> 01:32:45,324
<i>Got pushed down into the Florida</i>
<i>Everglades back in pioneer days.

1243
01:32:46,121 --> 01:32:49,074
African people run off from slaveholders...

1244
01:32:49,457 --> 01:32:51,033
...hooked up with them...

1245
01:32:51,124 --> 01:32:53,282
...married up, had children.

1246
01:32:54,542 --> 01:32:57,292
When the Spanish gave up Florida...

1247
01:32:57,376 --> 01:33:00,957
<i>...the U.S. Army come down</i>
<i>to move all the Indian people to Oklahoma.

1248
01:33:01,170 --> 01:33:02,664
<i>A couple of them held out.

1249
01:33:03,046 --> 01:33:05,203
That man, John Horse...

1250
01:33:05,297 --> 01:33:07,787
...his friend, Wildcat, another fella named...

1251
01:33:07,882 --> 01:33:09,209
<i>...Osceola...

1252
01:33:09,424 --> 01:33:11,083
<i>...formed a fighting band...

1253
01:33:11,175 --> 01:33:14,127
...held out for another 10, 15 years...

1254
01:33:14,593 --> 01:33:18,505
...and beat zach Taylor and 1,000 troops
at Lake Okeechobee.

1255
01:33:20,429 --> 01:33:22,053
So they stayed in Florida?

1256
01:33:22,138 --> 01:33:25,174
OTIS: One night they packed up,
rode out to Mexico.

1257
01:33:26,307 --> 01:33:29,508
Men went to work
for General Santa Anna down there.

1258
01:33:31,100 --> 01:33:35,476
After the Civil War they came north
to Texas, put up at Fort Duncan...

1259
01:33:35,812 --> 01:33:40,222
...and the men joined what was called
the Seminole Negro Indian Scouts.

1260
01:33:40,480 --> 01:33:41,642
The best trackers...

1261
01:33:41,731 --> 01:33:45,513
<i>...on either side of the border.</i>
<i>They chased after bandits...

1262
01:33:46,149 --> 01:33:49,766
...rustlers, Texas rednecks,
Kiowas, Comanches....

1263
01:33:50,360 --> 01:33:52,565
They fought against the Indians?

1264
01:33:52,653 --> 01:33:54,229
Just like they did in Mexico.

1265
01:33:54,320 --> 01:33:56,110
But they were Indians themselves.

1266
01:33:57,030 --> 01:33:58,772
They were in the Army...

1267
01:33:59,031 --> 01:34:00,524
...like your father.

1268
01:34:03,616 --> 01:34:05,275
You know who I am?

1269
01:34:07,284 --> 01:34:09,193
I got a pretty good guess.

1270
01:34:10,161 --> 01:34:11,441
That guy who got shot.

1271
01:34:12,620 --> 01:34:15,324
You didn't go telling your father
you were here?

1272
01:34:15,497 --> 01:34:16,824
Are you kidding?

1273
01:34:17,331 --> 01:34:19,157
And face a court-martial?

1274
01:34:21,750 --> 01:34:22,994
Pretty tough old man.

1275
01:34:23,584 --> 01:34:25,410
Every time he moves up a rank...

1276
01:34:25,502 --> 01:34:28,501
<i>...he tightens the screws a little more.</i>
<i>Just 'cause....

1277
01:34:29,711 --> 01:34:31,537
You know, he didn't have....

1278
01:34:33,672 --> 01:34:35,295
Didn't have a father.

1279
01:34:36,966 --> 01:34:38,956
He's still pissed off about it.

1280
01:34:41,175 --> 01:34:42,918
When you're his age...

1281
01:34:44,344 --> 01:34:47,011
...you'll still be pissed off about him.

1282
01:34:51,222 --> 01:34:53,012
How come you got into this?

1283
01:34:55,974 --> 01:34:57,717
These are our people.

1284
01:34:58,350 --> 01:35:02,216
There are Paynes in Florida,
Oklahoma, Piedras Negras--

1285
01:35:03,061 --> 01:35:04,341
So I'm part Indian?

1286
01:35:04,854 --> 01:35:06,513
By blood you are.

1287
01:35:07,980 --> 01:35:09,888
But blood only means what you let it.

1288
01:35:10,565 --> 01:35:14,560
My father says from the day you're born
you start from scratch.

1289
01:35:15,525 --> 01:35:16,390
No breaks.

1290
01:35:16,484 --> 01:35:17,598
<i>No excuses.

1291
01:35:19,694 --> 01:35:21,935
You got to pull yourself up on your own.

1292
01:35:22,903 --> 01:35:25,228
He's living proof of that, son.

1293
01:35:27,406 --> 01:35:28,899
Living proof.

1294
01:35:37,077 --> 01:35:38,570
'Morning, Hollis.

1295
01:35:38,745 --> 01:35:39,775
Sam!

1296
01:35:39,870 --> 01:35:41,150
Sit down.

1297
01:35:42,455 --> 01:35:44,446
HOLLIS: Big to-do the other day.

1298
01:35:45,789 --> 01:35:48,160
Meant a lot to folks you said something.

1299
01:35:48,999 --> 01:35:51,037
You thought anymore about our murder?

1300
01:35:52,917 --> 01:35:56,783
I wish I could tell you I remembered
something new, but I can't.

1301
01:36:00,171 --> 01:36:02,495
Well, I got an idea what happened.

1302
01:36:02,881 --> 01:36:03,911
HOLLIS: You do?

1303
01:36:06,507 --> 01:36:10,633
I think somewhere between
Roderick Bledsoe's club and his house...

1304
01:36:10,718 --> 01:36:12,875
...Wade ran into Buddy Deeds.

1305
01:36:13,844 --> 01:36:16,001
I think Buddy put a bullet in him.

1306
01:36:16,345 --> 01:36:19,843
<i>Waited for him to die,</i>
<i>threw him in the trunk of the sheriff's car...

1307
01:36:19,930 --> 01:36:22,385
<i>...and drove him out by Fort McKenzie.

1308
01:36:23,891 --> 01:36:27,886
I think he buried him under four feet
of sand and never looked back.

1309
01:36:32,561 --> 01:36:34,849
You lived in the man's house, how long?

1310
01:36:35,854 --> 01:36:37,681
17, 18 years...

1311
01:36:39,023 --> 01:36:42,105
...but didn't get to know him
any better than that.

1312
01:36:43,108 --> 01:36:46,060
I got to go see somebody
up in San Antonio.

1313
01:36:48,319 --> 01:36:50,643
Now, your memory gets any better...

1314
01:36:50,862 --> 01:36:52,853
...I'll be back tonight.

1315
01:37:06,911 --> 01:37:08,618
PALOMA: She finally got up.

1316
01:37:09,995 --> 01:37:11,406
It's Saturday.

1317
01:37:11,913 --> 01:37:13,703
You got in late last night.

1318
01:37:14,122 --> 01:37:15,532
I had some...

1319
01:37:16,457 --> 01:37:18,330
...some school business.

1320
01:37:20,918 --> 01:37:22,162
Could I get this?

1321
01:37:23,919 --> 01:37:24,997
Paloma.

1322
01:37:25,378 --> 01:37:27,499
Nobody really wears that stuff.

1323
01:37:27,879 --> 01:37:31,044
Just 'cause you went to Catholic school
and wore a uniform.

1324
01:37:31,130 --> 01:37:33,455
I only went for my last two years.

1325
01:37:33,924 --> 01:37:35,251
PALOMA: How come?

1326
01:37:37,467 --> 01:37:40,086
My mother wanted
to keep me away from...

1327
01:37:42,844 --> 01:37:44,088
...from boys.

1328
01:37:45,012 --> 01:37:46,340
PALOMA: Did it work?

1329
01:37:50,181 --> 01:37:53,382
Longhorns go for 10 times the price.

1330
01:37:54,850 --> 01:37:57,600
But longhorns are hard
to come by these days.

1331
01:37:58,644 --> 01:38:00,102
Sell much out here?

1332
01:38:00,687 --> 01:38:03,639
How am I going to sell things?
Nobody comes around.

1333
01:38:03,979 --> 01:38:05,722
This stretch of road...

1334
01:38:05,814 --> 01:38:08,101
...runs between Nowhere and...

1335
01:38:08,773 --> 01:38:10,314
...Not Much Else.

1336
01:38:11,108 --> 01:38:13,265
A hell of a spot to put a business.

1337
01:38:13,984 --> 01:38:16,189
Don't see much competition, do you?

1338
01:38:17,403 --> 01:38:19,856
Used to sell these things like hotcakes.

1339
01:38:19,945 --> 01:38:21,107
Now...

1340
01:38:21,529 --> 01:38:24,861
...if it can't play those disks,
they won't look at it.

1341
01:38:26,198 --> 01:38:27,691
I like it here.

1342
01:38:28,658 --> 01:38:31,408
Once I tried going
onto the reservation to live.

1343
01:38:31,492 --> 01:38:33,282
Couldn't take the politics.

1344
01:38:33,368 --> 01:38:36,202
Damn Indians will drive you crazy
with that.

1345
01:38:39,246 --> 01:38:42,613
Now, your father,
this wasn't what he had in mind.

1346
01:38:43,957 --> 01:38:45,616
He come out of Korea...

1347
01:38:45,749 --> 01:38:48,582
...bought a Chevy with too much engine.

1348
01:38:49,042 --> 01:38:53,832
Used to come roaring up and down
this road all hours of the day and night...

1349
01:38:54,086 --> 01:38:56,161
...looking for somebody to race.

1350
01:39:01,673 --> 01:39:02,669
WESLEY: Here.

1351
01:39:04,008 --> 01:39:05,631
Buffalo chips.

1352
01:39:06,175 --> 01:39:07,966
<i>A fella down in Santa Fe told me...

1353
01:39:08,051 --> 01:39:11,798
...he sells these as fast
as a buffalo can squeeze them out.

1354
01:39:17,764 --> 01:39:20,432
You think he killed anybody in Korea?

1355
01:39:21,683 --> 01:39:25,513
They don't hand those medals out
for hiding in your foxhole.

1356
01:39:28,394 --> 01:39:29,852
Would you buy this?

1357
01:39:32,187 --> 01:39:33,135
No.

1358
01:39:34,439 --> 01:39:36,347
Yeah, neither would I.

1359
01:39:38,190 --> 01:39:40,893
If he hadn't found the deputy's job...

1360
01:39:42,026 --> 01:39:46,566
...I believe Buddy might've gone down
the other path, got into serious trouble.

1361
01:39:47,069 --> 01:39:48,860
It settled him right down.

1362
01:39:48,945 --> 01:39:50,688
That and your mother.

1363
01:39:54,865 --> 01:39:57,236
Of course, he had that other one later.

1364
01:40:06,871 --> 01:40:08,447
He had another woman?

1365
01:40:10,331 --> 01:40:14,243
Your mother was not one
to be chased off her patch.

1366
01:40:14,916 --> 01:40:17,406
Half the damn county knew about it.

1367
01:40:18,251 --> 01:40:21,618
Nobody thought the worse of her
for seeing it through.

1368
01:40:21,711 --> 01:40:23,335
You know who it was?

1369
01:40:24,086 --> 01:40:25,415
The other one?

1370
01:40:26,171 --> 01:40:27,036
At my age...

1371
01:40:27,547 --> 01:40:28,957
<i>...you learn a new name...

1372
01:40:29,048 --> 01:40:31,039
...you got to forget an old one.

1373
01:40:31,549 --> 01:40:32,544
WESLEY: Here.

1374
01:40:34,800 --> 01:40:38,499
This big fella was sleeping
in a crate at Cisco's junkyard.

1375
01:40:39,011 --> 01:40:42,176
When I was going to open
to see what was in her...

1376
01:40:42,471 --> 01:40:44,628
...jumped right at my face.

1377
01:40:45,680 --> 01:40:49,094
Scared me so bad I had to kill him
without thinking.

1378
01:40:49,599 --> 01:40:53,381
Be careful where you go poking.
Who knows what you'll find.

1379
01:41:32,369 --> 01:41:33,945
Private Johnson...

1380
01:41:36,663 --> 01:41:38,868
...are you unhappy...

1381
01:41:39,747 --> 01:41:40,862
...in the Army?

1382
01:41:41,082 --> 01:41:42,195
No, sir.

1383
01:41:43,707 --> 01:41:45,829
Then how would you explain...

1384
01:41:46,042 --> 01:41:48,247
...that out of 120 people...

1385
01:41:48,377 --> 01:41:50,285
...you were the only one...

1386
01:41:50,378 --> 01:41:52,665
<i>...who tested positive for drugs?

1387
01:41:52,753 --> 01:41:54,295
I'm sorry, sir.

1388
01:41:56,630 --> 01:41:59,464
When you were given
the opportunity to enlist...

1389
01:41:59,924 --> 01:42:03,172
...a kind of contract was agreed upon.

1390
01:42:03,259 --> 01:42:06,092
I think the Army has honored its part...

1391
01:42:06,218 --> 01:42:07,463
...of that agreement.

1392
01:42:07,553 --> 01:42:08,547
Yes, sir.

1393
01:42:08,678 --> 01:42:11,346
Do you believe in what we do
in here, Private?

1394
01:42:11,971 --> 01:42:13,843
I can do the job, sir.

1395
01:42:20,892 --> 01:42:24,390
What exactly do you think your job is?

1396
01:42:26,603 --> 01:42:29,009
Follow orders, do whatever they say.

1397
01:42:29,229 --> 01:42:30,426
DEL: Who's ''they''?

1398
01:42:31,564 --> 01:42:33,105
The officers.

1399
01:42:33,189 --> 01:42:34,730
And that's the job?

1400
01:42:35,566 --> 01:42:37,937
Nothing about serving your country?

1401
01:42:40,901 --> 01:42:43,651
These are not trick questions,
Private Johnson.

1402
01:42:44,069 --> 01:42:45,527
You'll get an Article 15...

1403
01:42:45,611 --> 01:42:48,813
<i>...and we'll go through the process</i>
<i>one way or another.

1404
01:42:49,446 --> 01:42:51,853
I'm just trying to understand...

1405
01:42:53,240 --> 01:42:55,564
...how someone like you thinks.

1406
01:42:56,742 --> 01:42:58,533
You really want to know?

1407
01:42:58,701 --> 01:42:59,696
Please.

1408
01:43:02,203 --> 01:43:06,199
It's their country. This is one
of the best deals they offer.

1409
01:43:08,706 --> 01:43:11,030
How do you think I got to be a colonel?

1410
01:43:11,416 --> 01:43:13,987
Being good at your job.
Doing what they tell you.

1411
01:43:14,083 --> 01:43:15,494
Do what they tell you?

1412
01:43:15,585 --> 01:43:17,622
I mean, follow orders, sir.

1413
01:43:22,087 --> 01:43:24,411
With your attitude, Private...

1414
01:43:25,255 --> 01:43:27,710
...I'm surprised you want to stay
in the service.

1415
01:43:28,257 --> 01:43:29,454
I do, sir.

1416
01:43:30,216 --> 01:43:31,544
Because it's a job?

1417
01:43:33,885 --> 01:43:36,375
Outside it's such a mess. It's....

1418
01:43:41,138 --> 01:43:42,086
Chaos.

1419
01:43:45,432 --> 01:43:46,890
Why do you think...

1420
01:43:48,933 --> 01:43:51,258
...they let us in on the deal?

1421
01:43:54,895 --> 01:43:59,554
'Cause they got people to fight:
Arabs, yellow people, whatever.

1422
01:43:59,646 --> 01:44:01,437
Might as well use us.

1423
01:44:09,067 --> 01:44:11,059
It works like this, Private.

1424
01:44:11,903 --> 01:44:15,352
Every soldier in the war
doesn't have to believe...

1425
01:44:15,821 --> 01:44:17,729
...in what he's fighting for.

1426
01:44:18,530 --> 01:44:22,989
Most of them fight just to back up
the other soldiers in their squad.

1427
01:44:24,241 --> 01:44:26,233
You try not to get them killed.

1428
01:44:26,326 --> 01:44:28,732
You try not to get them extra duty.

1429
01:44:29,077 --> 01:44:31,531
You try not embarrass yourself...

1430
01:44:32,329 --> 01:44:33,822
...in front of them.

1431
01:44:47,878 --> 01:44:49,870
Why don't you start with that?

1432
01:44:50,879 --> 01:44:51,957
Yes, sir.

1433
01:44:56,298 --> 01:44:57,461
Dismissed.

1434
01:44:59,300 --> 01:45:00,758
Thank you, sir.

1435
01:45:28,146 --> 01:45:29,177
ENRIQUE: [In Spanish ]

1436
01:45:30,314 --> 01:45:31,227
ANSELMA:

1437
01:45:37,026 --> 01:45:41,436
ANNOUNCER: <i>Fred Zenito for Pager</i>
<i>and the Aggies jump to a 1 4-point lead.

1438
01:45:41,569 --> 01:45:43,894
<i>Sooners back to punt on their own 27.

1439
01:45:45,279 --> 01:45:49,904
Longhorns are going to kick some serious
butt this Saturday. You just watch.

1440
01:45:50,241 --> 01:45:54,318
We got a kid, a tailback from
down your way, out of El Indio--

1441
01:45:54,867 --> 01:45:56,408
That's in Maverick County.

1442
01:45:56,993 --> 01:45:58,487
Right, and you're in?

1443
01:45:58,577 --> 01:45:59,609
In Rio.

1444
01:45:59,869 --> 01:46:01,695
This kid, Hosea Brown...

1445
01:46:01,787 --> 01:46:03,281
...he does the 40 in 3.4.

1446
01:46:03,372 --> 01:46:06,122
Soft hands, lateral movement,
the whole package.

1447
01:46:06,206 --> 01:46:08,778
-Only a sophomore.
-Still go to all the home games?

1448
01:46:08,874 --> 01:46:12,870
Daddy's got his box in the stadium
and I'll fly to the Cowboy away games.

1449
01:46:13,334 --> 01:46:15,789
<i>And Friday nights there's high school.

1450
01:46:15,877 --> 01:46:19,540
Churchill's got this boy, 6 foot 6,
310, moves like a cat.

1451
01:46:19,712 --> 01:46:23,245
High school, we're talking.
Guess how much he can bench-press?

1452
01:46:23,714 --> 01:46:25,042
Bunny, you....

1453
01:46:25,674 --> 01:46:27,464
You on that same medication?

1454
01:46:27,717 --> 01:46:29,542
-Why, do I seem jumpy?
-No.

1455
01:46:29,884 --> 01:46:32,124
You look good. I was just wondering.

1456
01:46:32,593 --> 01:46:36,292
BUNNY: Last year was awful with Mama
passing on and this business with O.J.

1457
01:46:36,387 --> 01:46:38,295
<i>It's not Don Meredith or...

1458
01:46:38,388 --> 01:46:41,470
...one of our boys,
but it kind of threw me for a loop.

1459
01:46:41,723 --> 01:46:43,003
You look good.

1460
01:46:43,557 --> 01:46:46,177
Then that squeaker,
the Aggies dropped to Oklahoma.

1461
01:46:46,267 --> 01:46:50,393
That son of a bitch stepped in some
lucky shit before he kicked that goal.

1462
01:46:50,768 --> 01:46:54,550
If they hadn't pulled me off that woman,
I'd have jerked a knot in her.

1463
01:46:56,230 --> 01:46:57,771
Were you in a fight?

1464
01:46:58,772 --> 01:47:01,060
Daddy calls it an altercation.

1465
01:47:01,858 --> 01:47:04,144
How you doing, Sam? You look skinny.

1466
01:47:04,775 --> 01:47:07,396
No, I'm the same weight I always was.

1467
01:47:08,777 --> 01:47:11,895
Daddy hired a pinhead to take your job.
Says so himself:

1468
01:47:12,112 --> 01:47:15,313
<i>''Even my son-in-law was better</i>
<i>than this pinhead I got now. ''

1469
01:47:15,405 --> 01:47:16,520
Bunny....

1470
01:47:18,866 --> 01:47:21,437
That stuff I left in the garage still there?

1471
01:47:22,950 --> 01:47:26,649
Least he never called me that.
With me it was always ''high-strung.''

1472
01:47:26,744 --> 01:47:30,360
''Bunny would've done something
with her life if she wasn't so high-strung.''

1473
01:47:30,454 --> 01:47:32,078
Or ''tightly wound.''

1474
01:47:32,705 --> 01:47:35,242
You haven't had one of your fires,
have you?

1475
01:47:36,415 --> 01:47:40,280
The stuff I left in the garage,
some of it was my father's.

1476
01:47:41,084 --> 01:47:43,040
Did you watch the draft this year?

1477
01:47:44,627 --> 01:47:47,911
Of course not. Idiot question.
They try to make it dramatic...

1478
01:47:48,004 --> 01:47:50,920
...like it's a surprise who picks who
in the first round...

1479
01:47:51,005 --> 01:47:55,332
...but they went over it for months
with their experts, computers...

1480
01:47:55,549 --> 01:47:58,548
...doctor's reports, coach's evaluations...

1481
01:47:58,717 --> 01:48:02,132
...highlight reels, psychological profiles....

1482
01:48:02,886 --> 01:48:07,711
I wouldn't be surprised if they collected
stool samples on them, had them analyzed.

1483
01:48:07,889 --> 01:48:09,299
All that to pick...

1484
01:48:09,389 --> 01:48:11,595
...a football player for your squad.

1485
01:48:12,515 --> 01:48:16,807
Compared to that, what you know about
a person when you get married to them...

1486
01:48:16,893 --> 01:48:19,346
...doesn't amount to diddly, does it?

1487
01:48:22,187 --> 01:48:23,894
No, I suppose not.

1488
01:48:24,396 --> 01:48:28,012
You kind of bought yourself
a pig in a poke, didn't you?

1489
01:48:29,065 --> 01:48:33,974
The whole time we were seeing each other,
you didn't know that I was tightly wound.

1490
01:48:34,360 --> 01:48:36,350
It wasn't just you, Bunny.

1491
01:48:37,402 --> 01:48:39,228
No, it wasn't, was it?

1492
01:48:40,612 --> 01:48:44,193
You didn't exactly throw yourself
into it heart and soul.

1493
01:48:47,240 --> 01:48:50,821
Your shit's still in the garage,
if that's what you came for.

1494
01:49:03,081 --> 01:49:05,072
Three hundred and fifty pounds.

1495
01:49:09,042 --> 01:49:12,907
That boy Churchill's got.
He plays tackle both ways.

1496
01:49:15,420 --> 01:49:17,661
Bench-presses 350 pounds.

1497
01:49:20,547 --> 01:49:23,463
Imagine having that much weight on you,
pressing down.

1498
01:49:23,548 --> 01:49:26,217
Be hard to breathe, hard to swallow.

1499
01:49:27,592 --> 01:49:31,504
I think they have another fella there
to keep it off your chest.

1500
01:49:33,553 --> 01:49:34,716
A spotter.

1501
01:49:35,805 --> 01:49:39,302
''I only got my little girl now,'' he says.

1502
01:49:39,515 --> 01:49:41,222
''She's my lifeline.''

1503
01:49:43,100 --> 01:49:47,047
Then he says I can't sit in the box anymore
if I don't control myself.

1504
01:49:47,560 --> 01:49:48,591
Son of a bitch!

1505
01:49:48,686 --> 01:49:51,768
<i>He doesn't even watch the games,</i>
<i>just sits there drinking.

1506
01:49:51,853 --> 01:49:53,513
Looks up at the TV now and then.

1507
01:49:53,604 --> 01:49:57,304
I'd be better off in the cheap seats
with some real football people.

1508
01:49:58,190 --> 01:49:59,849
You look good, Bunny.

1509
01:50:01,275 --> 01:50:03,065
It was nice to see you.

1510
01:50:05,735 --> 01:50:06,731
Thanks.

1511
01:50:08,612 --> 01:50:11,101
I like it when you say that, Sam.

1512
01:50:36,458 --> 01:50:38,035
''Dearest Buddy.''

1513
01:50:49,047 --> 01:50:50,754
CAROLYN: Hey, it's the general.

1514
01:50:52,465 --> 01:50:54,753
Colonel. Is Otis in?

1515
01:50:54,925 --> 01:50:56,584
-Come on in.
-If it's too late--

1516
01:50:56,676 --> 01:50:57,920
Come on in.

1517
01:51:06,556 --> 01:51:10,883
Otis is sitting up with some people
at the club. I don't think he'll be long.

1518
01:51:19,020 --> 01:51:22,103
His hot sauce recipe
won a contest last year.

1519
01:51:22,521 --> 01:51:24,264
They're selling it as far away...

1520
01:51:24,355 --> 01:51:25,731
...as San Antonio.

1521
01:51:26,732 --> 01:51:29,269
You've been in this house for a while?

1522
01:51:30,025 --> 01:51:34,400
I've been here with him eight years.
He built it when he was with Leora.

1523
01:51:35,361 --> 01:51:36,736
Never met her.

1524
01:51:37,570 --> 01:51:39,894
There's a bunch of them you never met.

1525
01:51:40,071 --> 01:51:41,730
Well, me neither.

1526
01:51:43,573 --> 01:51:45,897
Let me show you around.

1527
01:52:01,040 --> 01:52:04,407
He got into this cowboys-and-Indians stuff
a while back.

1528
01:52:04,708 --> 01:52:06,249
Spent half his time poking...

1529
01:52:06,334 --> 01:52:08,740
...around the library, way up to Austin.

1530
01:52:12,587 --> 01:52:14,543
[Soft instrumental music]

1531
01:52:29,553 --> 01:52:31,592
Kind of like a shrine, isn't it?

1532
01:52:33,764 --> 01:52:35,801
Where did he get all this stuff?

1533
01:52:35,972 --> 01:52:37,928
Your mother's got a brother, Alphonse.

1534
01:52:38,807 --> 01:52:39,672
Uncle Al.

1535
01:52:39,766 --> 01:52:43,596
CAROLYN: Otis stood on good terms
with him. Whenever you make the news...

1536
01:52:43,726 --> 01:52:45,101
...he sends it on.

1537
01:52:45,769 --> 01:52:47,725
When they made you general...

1538
01:52:47,937 --> 01:52:50,723
...Otis almost drove away
our customers going on about it.

1539
01:52:50,813 --> 01:52:52,141
I'm a colonel.

1540
01:52:52,731 --> 01:52:53,726
I know.

1541
01:52:54,398 --> 01:52:57,267
The man made me memorize
the whole Army chain of command...

1542
01:52:57,358 --> 01:52:59,065
...before he'd marry me.

1543
01:53:03,194 --> 01:53:05,945
My mother said that
he never asked about me.

1544
01:53:07,363 --> 01:53:09,022
He never asked her.

1545
01:53:19,660 --> 01:53:21,236
Tell him I stopped by?

1546
01:53:21,869 --> 01:53:22,947
Thanks.

1547
01:53:27,455 --> 01:53:28,735
Catch you later...

1548
01:53:30,581 --> 01:53:31,744
...Colonel.

1549
01:53:36,835 --> 01:53:37,748
[Anselma screams]

1550
01:53:37,836 --> 01:53:38,866
ANSELMA: [In Spanish ]

1551
01:53:39,795 --> 01:53:40,743
JAIME:

1552
01:53:49,423 --> 01:53:50,337
ENRIQUE:

1553
01:53:57,803 --> 01:53:58,716
ANSELMA:

1554
01:54:04,514 --> 01:54:06,589
ENRIQUE: <i>Señora Cruz.

1555
01:54:08,432 --> 01:54:09,547
MERCEDES: Who is it?

1556
01:54:09,642 --> 01:54:10,506
ENRIQUE: [In Spanish ]

1557
01:54:13,477 --> 01:54:16,476
What are you doing out here?
Are you crazy?

1558
01:54:20,856 --> 01:54:23,523
In English. We're in the United States.

1559
01:54:23,773 --> 01:54:27,520
I have some friends
and they have had an accident.

1560
01:54:28,818 --> 01:54:31,307
-You have somebody else out there?
-We was...

1561
01:54:31,402 --> 01:54:35,148
...by the river and I heard my friend
calling for help...

1562
01:54:35,696 --> 01:54:37,070
<i>...and I look...

1563
01:54:37,613 --> 01:54:39,522
...and she has fallen in the water.

1564
01:54:39,614 --> 01:54:41,606
Don't tell me lies. What happened?

1565
01:54:43,283 --> 01:54:45,440
We was crossing the river.

1566
01:54:51,036 --> 01:54:52,945
MERCEDES: What are you doing out there?

1567
01:54:53,079 --> 01:54:55,449
Wait. Who are they?
Why bring them here?

1568
01:54:55,705 --> 01:54:57,246
ENRIQUE: I need help, <i>señora</i>.

1569
01:54:57,998 --> 01:54:58,911
[In Spanish ]

1570
01:55:02,876 --> 01:55:05,910
I'll call Border Patrol.
They'll get her to the hospital.

1571
01:55:06,002 --> 01:55:06,997
ENRIQUE:

1572
01:55:07,502 --> 01:55:09,909
You think you're doing
these people a favor?

1573
01:55:10,004 --> 01:55:12,753
What are they going to do?
They get on welfare...

1574
01:55:12,838 --> 01:55:14,664
...or they become criminals.

1575
01:55:14,755 --> 01:55:16,297
[In Spanish ]

1576
01:55:40,809 --> 01:55:42,765
This girl is a friend of yours?

1577
01:55:44,770 --> 01:55:46,263
I thought you were married.

1578
01:55:46,479 --> 01:55:50,688
I am married to the cousin of a friend
but only to live here.

1579
01:55:51,148 --> 01:55:52,938
This is the mother of my child.

1580
01:55:54,775 --> 01:55:55,805
Typical.

1581
01:56:06,238 --> 01:56:07,317
Homework?

1582
01:56:09,114 --> 01:56:10,656
I finished that.

1583
01:56:10,948 --> 01:56:12,608
I'm just messing around.

1584
01:56:16,785 --> 01:56:17,899
Tanks, huh?

1585
01:56:18,577 --> 01:56:19,905
Yeah, well....

1586
01:56:20,369 --> 01:56:24,033
If you've got to be in the Army,
better to have something slick to drive.

1587
01:56:24,121 --> 01:56:25,117
So....

1588
01:56:26,372 --> 01:56:28,115
You're going in the Army?

1589
01:56:30,875 --> 01:56:32,997
That's the general plan, isn't it?

1590
01:56:38,420 --> 01:56:39,913
That's up to you.

1591
01:56:44,006 --> 01:56:46,164
The Army isn't for everybody.

1592
01:56:53,427 --> 01:56:56,260
It's not that I think
you wouldn't be good at it.

1593
01:56:56,762 --> 01:56:57,924
<i>You know....

1594
01:57:00,222 --> 01:57:04,632
I wouldn't be disappointed if you decided
to do something else with your life.

1595
01:57:07,392 --> 01:57:08,423
You wouldn't?

1596
01:57:10,894 --> 01:57:11,842
No.

1597
01:57:20,190 --> 01:57:21,304
So....

1598
01:57:23,066 --> 01:57:25,057
How's your room shaping up?

1599
01:57:26,692 --> 01:57:28,850
It's fine. I'm pretty much moved in.

1600
01:57:28,944 --> 01:57:30,105
DEL: Good.

1601
01:57:35,447 --> 01:57:37,403
Are we ever going to see your father?

1602
01:57:37,948 --> 01:57:39,110
My father?

1603
01:57:39,448 --> 01:57:40,693
He lives here, right?

1604
01:57:40,783 --> 01:57:41,945
Yes, he does.

1605
01:57:48,787 --> 01:57:50,280
Maybe we'll....

1606
01:57:50,954 --> 01:57:53,870
We'll fix that thing out back and have...

1607
01:57:54,289 --> 01:57:55,320
...a barbecue.

1608
01:57:56,040 --> 01:57:57,699
<i>We could invite him and...

1609
01:57:57,791 --> 01:57:59,450
...and his wife over.

1610
01:58:02,668 --> 01:58:04,494
He makes his own sauce.

1611
01:58:06,837 --> 01:58:08,246
[In Spanish ]

1612
01:58:15,882 --> 01:58:16,712
ELADIO:

1613
01:59:03,071 --> 01:59:05,193
[In Spanish ] <i>Let's go! Hurry up!

1614
01:59:05,906 --> 01:59:08,360
Everybody in the world will see.

1615
01:59:11,159 --> 01:59:12,985
He was a doctor on the other side.

1616
01:59:14,910 --> 01:59:16,320
MERCEDES: Don't worry about it.

1617
01:59:17,786 --> 01:59:19,612
He owes me a few favors.

1618
01:59:20,246 --> 01:59:21,526
ENRIQUE: [In Spanish ]

1619
01:59:25,457 --> 01:59:28,243
In English, Enrique. In English!

1620
01:59:34,794 --> 01:59:35,826
SAM: [Shouts] Hollis!

1621
01:59:40,006 --> 01:59:41,001
Hollis!

1622
01:59:43,341 --> 01:59:44,798
You in there?

1623
02:00:09,603 --> 02:00:10,598
Fellas.

1624
02:00:18,607 --> 02:00:20,100
You're open late.

1625
02:00:20,858 --> 02:00:23,608
I'm not open. We're just talking.

1626
02:00:31,279 --> 02:00:33,271
So, Hollis probably told you.

1627
02:00:33,906 --> 02:00:35,779
We found Charlie Wade.

1628
02:00:36,740 --> 02:00:38,234
Is that right?

1629
02:00:39,367 --> 02:00:42,816
Start digging holes in this county,
no telling what'll come up.

1630
02:00:44,786 --> 02:00:46,694
You two saw it, didn't you?

1631
02:00:49,622 --> 02:00:52,111
You two saw it when Buddy killed him.

1632
02:00:56,124 --> 02:00:58,614
I'm going to find out one way or the other.

1633
02:00:59,251 --> 02:01:02,286
Your father had the finest sense
of justice...

1634
02:01:02,461 --> 02:01:04,417
...of any man I've ever known.

1635
02:01:04,921 --> 02:01:06,911
And my mother was a saint.

1636
02:01:09,130 --> 02:01:11,881
For 15 years the whole damn town...

1637
02:01:12,216 --> 02:01:14,883
...knew he had another woman on the side.

1638
02:01:18,468 --> 02:01:21,172
He stole $10,000
and set her up in business...

1639
02:01:21,303 --> 02:01:23,046
...but hell, what's that?

1640
02:01:23,805 --> 02:01:26,128
You got a problem, old Buddy'll fix it.

1641
02:01:26,639 --> 02:01:28,844
You facing some time in jail?

1642
02:01:29,057 --> 02:01:33,135
Buddy'll knock half of it off,
if you do what he says when he says.

1643
02:01:34,393 --> 02:01:37,013
You got some business
that's not exactly legal?

1644
02:01:37,102 --> 02:01:38,300
Just talk to Buddy.

1645
02:01:38,395 --> 02:01:39,425
Buddy Deeds--

1646
02:01:39,520 --> 02:01:41,346
Buddy Deeds was a murderer.

1647
02:01:43,313 --> 02:01:44,771
SAM: That night at the cafe...

1648
02:01:45,147 --> 02:01:48,313
...he didn't stay long after you left,
did he, Hollis?

1649
02:01:49,567 --> 02:01:52,601
Maybe he'd decided
he'd gone too far with Wade.

1650
02:01:52,693 --> 02:01:56,107
He figured he'd better not wait
for the sheriff to get behind him.

1651
02:01:56,194 --> 02:01:58,815
So he stepped out to see
if he could catch up...

1652
02:02:02,281 --> 02:02:04,771
...and you were here that night...

1653
02:02:05,365 --> 02:02:07,073
...weren't you, ''O''?

1654
02:02:08,993 --> 02:02:10,272
I was here.

1655
02:02:13,786 --> 02:02:17,118
I'd been running a game
on the side after hours.

1656
02:02:18,955 --> 02:02:20,200
Craps.

1657
02:02:20,914 --> 02:02:23,155
Draw poker on the weekends.

1658
02:02:24,708 --> 02:02:26,865
Roderick didn't know about it.

1659
02:02:27,751 --> 02:02:29,245
More important...

1660
02:02:29,836 --> 02:02:32,503
...Charlie Wade didn't know about it...

1661
02:02:32,879 --> 02:02:35,877
...'cause I didn't want to cut him in on it.

1662
02:02:37,630 --> 02:02:40,796
I was pretty full of myself
back in those days.

1663
02:02:42,008 --> 02:02:45,790
Hell, I just didn't expect the man so early.

1664
02:03:15,065 --> 02:03:17,436
[Loud instrumental music]

1665
02:03:38,951 --> 02:03:40,907
[Inaudible conversation]

1666
02:04:56,987 --> 02:04:57,936
[Shouts] Wade!

1667
02:05:43,885 --> 02:05:47,584
OTIS: Sheriff Charlie was the whip hand
for old Judge Tibbs...

1668
02:05:47,970 --> 02:05:50,839
<i>...who pretty much owned</i>
<i>this county back then.

1669
02:05:51,888 --> 02:05:53,796
<i>If the truth came out...

1670
02:05:54,432 --> 02:05:57,100
<i>...he wasn't going to go easy on Hollis.

1671
02:05:59,642 --> 02:06:02,393
I don't know why I trusted Buddy with it...

1672
02:06:03,811 --> 02:06:05,933
...don't know why he trusted me.

1673
02:06:09,313 --> 02:06:11,139
The first time I talked with him...

1674
02:06:11,231 --> 02:06:13,270
...was right there and then...

1675
02:06:14,274 --> 02:06:18,269
...with a dead white man leaking blood
on the floor between us.

1676
02:06:18,818 --> 02:06:22,766
The three of us cleaned up
and took him out by the post...

1677
02:06:23,487 --> 02:06:25,028
...and put him under.

1678
02:06:26,280 --> 02:06:28,271
I can't say I was much help.

1679
02:06:28,823 --> 02:06:30,649
And the $10,000?

1680
02:06:31,574 --> 02:06:33,150
Widow's benefits.

1681
02:06:33,867 --> 02:06:36,701
He figured it'd make
the disappearance look better.

1682
02:06:36,827 --> 02:06:40,609
And Mercedes was scraping by
after Charlie killed her man.

1683
02:06:42,121 --> 02:06:43,365
Buddy and her...

1684
02:06:43,455 --> 02:06:45,660
<i>...didn't get hooked up until later.

1685
02:06:46,539 --> 02:06:48,365
OTIS: Time went on...

1686
02:06:48,457 --> 02:06:50,532
...people liked the story we told...

1687
02:06:50,624 --> 02:06:53,245
...better than what the truth
might have been.

1688
02:06:54,460 --> 02:06:56,119
It's your call, Sam.

1689
02:06:58,128 --> 02:07:01,128
I don't think the Rangers are likely to...

1690
02:07:01,588 --> 02:07:04,422
...find out any more
than they already know.

1691
02:07:07,507 --> 02:07:09,166
And as for me...

1692
02:07:12,635 --> 02:07:15,469
...it's just one of your unsolved mysteries.

1693
02:07:24,724 --> 02:07:27,178
Word gets out who the body was...

1694
02:07:28,267 --> 02:07:30,389
...people'll think Buddy done it.

1695
02:07:33,686 --> 02:07:35,678
Buddy's a goddamn legend.

1696
02:07:37,521 --> 02:07:39,145
He can handle it.

1697
02:07:45,317 --> 02:07:46,810
SAM: 'Night, fellas.

1698
02:07:49,444 --> 02:07:51,815
[Soft instrumental music]

1699
02:07:56,781 --> 02:07:58,737
[Car engine rumbles]

1700
02:08:03,326 --> 02:08:05,897
[Car door opens and closes]

1701
02:08:14,748 --> 02:08:16,740
When does the picture start?

1702
02:08:19,917 --> 02:08:23,414
Are you going to tell your mother
we've been seeing each other?

1703
02:08:23,835 --> 02:08:26,041
She'll find out sooner or later.

1704
02:08:26,212 --> 02:08:29,828
I don't have to ask permission anymore,
if that's what you mean.

1705
02:08:35,882 --> 02:08:38,419
You have any idea when your father died?

1706
02:08:38,509 --> 02:08:39,503
Eladio?

1707
02:08:40,843 --> 02:08:43,131
Couple of months before I was born.

1708
02:08:45,720 --> 02:08:47,795
Try a year and half.

1709
02:09:07,523 --> 02:09:11,564
Buddy bought the cafe for her
with money he took from the county.

1710
02:09:15,317 --> 02:09:17,356
They can't pull this on me.

1711
02:09:18,486 --> 02:09:19,896
It's not fair.

1712
02:09:25,239 --> 02:09:26,815
I don't believe this.

1713
02:09:34,201 --> 02:09:37,118
He paid the hospital bill
when you were born.

1714
02:09:40,496 --> 02:09:41,775
Your mother...

1715
02:09:42,747 --> 02:09:44,655
...she always called you...

1716
02:09:45,124 --> 02:09:46,949
...''a beautiful daughter''...

1717
02:09:48,083 --> 02:09:50,288
...in the letters she wrote to him.

1718
02:09:57,504 --> 02:10:00,255
From the first time I saw you at school...

1719
02:10:10,051 --> 02:10:13,751
...all those years we were married
to other people, I always felt...

1720
02:10:14,846 --> 02:10:16,754
...like we were connected.

1721
02:10:21,682 --> 02:10:23,424
I remember thinking...

1722
02:10:25,100 --> 02:10:27,471
...you were the one part of my life...

1723
02:10:28,352 --> 02:10:30,558
...that Buddy didn't have a piece of.

1724
02:10:31,729 --> 02:10:34,016
I can't have any more children.

1725
02:10:34,688 --> 02:10:36,929
After Amado, I had complications.

1726
02:10:37,023 --> 02:10:40,603
I can't get pregnant anymore,
if that's what the rule is about.

1727
02:10:44,693 --> 02:10:46,020
So that's it?

1728
02:10:48,361 --> 02:10:50,851
You won't want to be with me anymore?

1729
02:10:54,489 --> 02:10:55,947
If I met you...

1730
02:10:57,699 --> 02:10:59,821
...for the first time today...

1731
02:11:01,117 --> 02:11:03,192
...I'd still want to be with you.

1732
02:11:08,829 --> 02:11:10,655
Start from scratch?

1733
02:11:12,123 --> 02:11:13,071
Yeah.

1734
02:11:14,790 --> 02:11:17,660
All that other stuff and all that history...

1735
02:11:18,584 --> 02:11:20,374
...the hell with it, right?

1736
02:11:26,379 --> 02:11:27,956
Forget the Alamo.

1737
02:11:42,678 --> 02:11:44,421
[Lively cowboy song]

1738
